<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAD-PAINT-PARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAD PAINT ON PLAY EQUIPMENT HAS L.A. PARKS OFFICIALS SCRAMBLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- City Recreation and Parks Department officials
are moving to shut off access at six parks because of potential
lead exposure from paint and released a list of more than 120 other
facilities with ratings of their paint conditions.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, officials said Thursday there has been no
indication of any child suffering illness from ingesting lead paint
at any of the city's park facilities. Childhood lead poisoning can
lead to brain damage, learning disabilities or a loss in IQ.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no need for anyone to panic,'' said Councilman Mike
Feuer, chairman of the City Council's Arts, Health and Humanities
Committee, who had asked for the report on the danger from lead
paint. ``What we are told by the Department of Health Services is
that problems develop only from long-term ingestion of lead
paint.''
</P>
<P>
   George Stigile, assistant general manager of the parks
department, said it was decided to close off buildings completely
rather than cordon off only problem areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to close the building rather than the entire
facility,'' Stigile said.
</P>
<P>
   The list of park facilities to be inspected had the six being
closed at the immediate-priority level. There were 58 in the
high-priority category, 27 in the medium-priority group, 11 in low
priority and 25 were listed as nonapplicable.
</P>
<P>
   But Feuer cautioned that the list might overstate the problem at
some facilities based on a cursory survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to release this to let the public know what's going
on,'' the councilman said. ``But some of these facilities might
have peeling paint that is not lead-based.''
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturing of lead paint was banned in 1978 by the
federal government, but it still can be found in wide use.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you live in a house built before 1978, there is probably
lead paint there,'' Stigile said. ``The same with office buildings.
What we are telling people is to take the same precautions as they
would in their own home.''
</P>
<P>
   Stigile said the department has contacted its lead-paint
consultants, who will work with the county Health Services
Department to further identify the problems at all city facilities
and determine where remedial work needs to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Feuer said his committee has set a Jan. 13 hearing to get more
information on the conditions and the level of work to be required.
</P>
<P>
   Parks Commission Chairman Steve Soboroff said the department has
received assurances that playground equipment is lead-free, but he
warned that there might still be problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of well-meaning people, and someone may have
painted a piece of equipment with lead-based paint and no one knew
about it,'' Soboroff said. ``But our main concern is public safety.
We have to go in there and make sure there is no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Feuer said health officials have told him the major problem is
for children under age 6 who crawl and could pick up lead paint or
dust and taste it.
</P>
<P>
   Stigile said recreation supervisors are on the alert for such
behavior and are monitoring children.
</P>
<P>
   Feuer, who had called for the assessment in July, said at the
time that he was disappointed by the lack of information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed that so little was known then since this
paint had been banned since 1978,'' he said, ``but I have been
pleased with the response since and the work going on to make our
children safe.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
