<HEADER>
A6498 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPT-PHOENIX-SPORTS-ME     12-25 2013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPT-PHOENIX-SPORTS-MECCA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE GOT GAMES 
 AREA BECOMES SPORTS HOTBED WITH FIESTA BOWL ON THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The millennium has arrived for metro Phoenix sports.
</P>
<P>
   With the Fiesta Bowl's fourth national-championship game in 13
years, Tempe will host the last of a long line of signature events
in the 1990s. Over the past decade, the Valley of the Sun has
undergone a meteoric rise in stature, from minor-league desert
outpost to sports mecca. And no one in the industry sees Jan. 4 as
the beginning of the end.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix still is in young sports adulthood and hungry for more.
Beyond the Fiesta Bowl on Jan. 4, look for events such as:
</P>
<P>
   The NHL All-Star Game, which Commissioner Gary Bettman promises
if the Coyotes get their own arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Major League Baseball All-Star Game, which is sure to come
to Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA Basketball Final Four, for which there are two
potential suitors: BOB, which aspires to host the first open-air
Final Four; and Rio Salado Crossing, a retractable-dome, removable
grass facility that the Cardinals are hoping to build.
</P>
<P>
   A spot in the regular Super Bowl rotation, which the Cardinals
believe would be a spinoff result of a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA Women's Basketball Final Four, which could come as soon
as 2003 or 2004 to America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   And further down the road, perhaps a realistic pursuit of the
Goodwill or Pan American games.
</P>
<P>
   The sports scene in the Valley, long the province of Arizona
State and the Suns, began to expand in the 1980s, with a couple of
national-championship Fiesta Bowls and the arrival of the Arizona
Cardinals from St. Louis in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The scene became more kaleidoscopic in the 1990s. America West
Arena opened in 1992, which led to an NBA All-Star Game in 1995.
January 1996 brought the Florida-Nebraska Fiesta Bowl title game,
followed by Super Bowl XXX. The Coyotes emigrated from Winnipeg in
1996, and the Diamondbacks began play in the $358 million Bank One
Ballpark in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``My take is Phoenix has been really positioned as a sports
city,'' said Rick Burton, director of the Warsaw Sports Marketing
Center at the University of Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   And the area's other assets _ a thriving economy, mild climate,
etc. _ will continue to make it an attractive sports locale.
</P>
<P>
   Burton says there are more benefits than what he sees as
inflated economic-impact reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of local pride or patriotism, it causes people to
believe, `I live someplace that is significant or meaningful.' I
view the sports stadium as the village green, where we used to
gather to celebrate our shared heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   That's similar to the message of Tostitos Fiesta Bowl Executive
Director John Junker, who says this year's first Bowl Championship
Series title game is predicted to have a direct economic impact of
$120 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're never here to argue about the last penny,'' Junker said.
``The issue is it's big, it's clean, it's fun, it's important, it's
generated by the hometown team of volunteers. And in order to keep
growing, there is going to need to be future commitments made.''
</P>
<P>
   That translates to facilities _ always a knotty issue when
taxpayers are asked to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   The $90 million America West Arena, which turns 7 next year,
remains a world-class venue to Suns President/CEO and Diamondbacks
Managing General Partner Jerry Colangelo, but recently has been
criticized for more than obstructed hockey seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a state-of-the-art building by today's standards,''
Coyotes defenseman Gerald Diduck has said.
</P>
<P>
   Central players &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes and the Cardinals are central players in the
uncertain future of Phoenix sports.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes are pushing a proposed $600 million renovation of
Los Arcos Mall in Scottsdale that would include a 20,000-seat
hockey arena.
</P>
<P>
   About six miles away, Mesa wants to build the $1.8 billion Rio
Salado Crossing with a 67,000-seat stadium with a retractable roof
and floor for the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Both proposals have their share of vocal detractors.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yes, Athletic Director Kevin White promises that Arizona
State ``will be the Number 1 physical plant in America'' within the
next decade, which will require up to $125 million in improvements
at 40-year-old Sun Devil Stadium _ not only for ASU's purposes but
to keep the Fiesta Bowl from relocating to Rio Salado Crossing,
should it come to pass. &QL; 
May votes likely
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo is out of the cross hairs on the new projects except
for his role as landlord to the Coyotes. But he's had a lot of
first-hand experience in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``These projects are a long way from reality at this point,''
Colangelo said. ``As it relates to the Cardinals, they've had this
great desire for their own new facility, and that package will be
very appealing to a number of people. It would be in their best
interest to have a new facility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As to the Coyotes, those issues can be resolved from what
we're understanding. But if that's their pleasure, that's their
pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious this (area) has been a proving ground of
developing concepts and partnerships. Anyone who follows with a
subsequent project has the advantage of looking back in what
transpired and the advantage of new forms of financing and
packaging.''
</P>
<P>
   Although significantly different in taxpayer demand, the Los
Arcos and Rio Salado Crossing projects will face a public vote,
both probably in May, something that neither Colangelo-run facility
had to hurdle. But the backlash price that Colangelo and elected
officials have paid for not going through the polls has been
bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a controversial issue since I've been here,'' said
Coyotes President Shawn Hunter. ``That issue is beginning to
dwindle and starting to soften as people experience America West
Arena and Bank One Ballpark. As people get a chance to visit the
venue, they're more comfortable with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it makes the Cardinals and Coyotes move forward
cautiously. It's caused us to take some wide turns that a lot of
teams and cities don't have to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``These projects are enormous and they take time. When you start
out, you have to be patient and develop a thick skin because not
everyone is as passionate as you are about the project.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Vice President Michael Bidwill senses a softening of
opposition to public funding to projects such as Rio Salado
Crossing, pointing to a recent poll of East Valley residents on the
convention center/stadium project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the more people learn about it, the more support it
gets, and that this will be successful,'' Bidwill said.
``Throughout the United States, voters are supporting
public-private partnerships to build facilities without as much
economic impact as Rio Salado. We're presenting a better package
than has been presented around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Hunter, Bidwill believes the amenities at America West
Arena and Bank One Ballpark are a significant selling point for the
new projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans have certainly benefited from those two buildings,
and it's also given both of those teams the opportunity to be
successful in acquiring free agents and maintaining their own
players,'' he said. ``Everybody loves Bank One Ballpark and
recognizes it is a huge success and a good idea to build. The
footnote is people didn't like the (funding) process. This process
is different.'' &QL; 
`Commitment to build'
</P>
<P>
   However the facility votes go, Phoenix, the newest of 10 markets
(Atlanta joins next year) with four major professional sports, has
enough variety on its sports platter to rival any of the other
nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's any coincidence that you have some
top-notch baseball talent signing to play here,'' Junker said.
``They can pick from six places, and it's not just because it's a
sunny place to live. It's a good place to live because there is a
commitment to growth, a commitment to service, a commitment to
build.''
</P>
<P>
   And the beat goes on:
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Open raises its purse to $3 million, one of richest
on the PGA Tour, with an eye toward joining the World Golf
Championship series.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix International Raceway approaches $300 million in annual
economic impact primarily for the West Valley, a lesser beneficiary
of much of the sports industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Cactus League hopes to attract the Los Angeles Dodgers to
add the crowning piece to a renaissance that has all 10 teams
playing in new or refurbished stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   And Arizona State, the only Division I university in the
nation's fastest-growing county, is in the midst of $25 million
athletic fund-raising drive (Sun Devil Stadium excepted) that will
return its physical plant to the stature of the late 1970s glory
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the potential to reclaim that position because of this
institution and the marketplace with its unique forces,'' said
White, coming up on the third anniversary of his hiring at ASU.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some tremendous professional sports operators, and
that's tremendous competition. At the same time, the demographics
(100,000 ASU alumni in Arizona, most in Maricopa County) are on our
side. Sports is pop culture in America today. We're at the right
place at exactly the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwill Games bid &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, too, could be the Maricopa County Sports Commission, which
is investigating ways to increase its annual budget of $750,000 and
become a genuine player in amateur sports bidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in some discussions with government and corporate
members who have a vision for this,'' said Herman Frazier, MCSC
chairman, a vice president of the U.S. Olympic Committee and
reigning President of the Fiesta Bowl. ``I'm optimistic we can get
to a point where we can bid on the Goodwill Games. We need to have
a multisport event.''
</P>
<P>
   The Goodwill Games, which brought 1,500 athletes from 60
countries to greater New York City last summer, are going to
Brisbane, Australia, in 2001 then returning to the United States in
2005.
</P>
<P>
   A 1986 creation of Ted Turner in response to the '80 and '84
Olympic boycotts, the Goodwill Games have reshaped themselves into
a television-friendly format for the most popular Olympic sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what we bring to the table in resources and assets, it
(Goodwill Games) has a lot of upside,'' said Mike Plant, Goodwill
Games president and vice president of Turner Sports. ``It can
behoove a city like Phoenix or any other city when a big machine
gets behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pan American Games, a much bigger and more expensive
operation, is second in size to only the Olympics (6,500 athletes
from 42 countries). They go from Winnipeg in 1999 to Santo Domingo,
Dominican Republic, in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio, North Carolina and South Florida are the U.S. areas
bidding for the 2007 games. If Phoenix can muster the support, it
could potentially bid on the 2015 games, a process that would begin
in 2005. &QL; 
New leaders emerge
</P>
<P>
   Who will lead the Phoenix sports movement into the future?
</P>
<P>
   The Valley sports leadership for the next decade ranges from
33-year-old Suns General Manager/Vice President Bryan Colangelo and
34-year-old Michael Bidwill to Junker, Frazier and White, all in
their 40s.
</P>
<P>
   At 67, Cardinals President Bill Bidwill is gratefully
relinquishing the public point-man duties he has never relished to
his son. But Jerry Colangelo, 35th on ``The Sporting News'' top 100
of the most powerful people in sports (Frazier is No. 70), is
hardly ready for pasture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 59 and feel 39,'' said Colangelo, who came to Phoenix in
1968 as the then-youngest general manager in NBA history. ``The way
I feel today, I plan to stay active for quite a long time. I feel
physically and mentally at the top of my game. If I were to lose
that passion and enthusiasm, it would be another story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been exciting to be part of this for 30 years. Most of
what's happened has been in the last decade, and that bodes well
for the future. There is tremendous upside for growth and
potential.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
