<HEADER>
A6499 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-RUNNER-BOSNIA-AZR     12-25 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUNNER-BOSNIA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW, HAPPY LIFE IN U.S. FOR CROATIAN TEENAGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - As the world watched the Baghdad night light up, the
guy whose St. Mary's High School family calls ``Z'' wanted no part
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd seen enough of it already,'' he told his legal guardian,
Donna Beardsley, who had asked if he wanted to watch the news
reports of the American missile strikes in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Zeljko Gavranovic, 17, a senior, headed to basketball
practice at St. Mary's gym, a world away from the place he left six
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He was 11, old enough to remember Croatia, the war, the bombs,
his father being killed by a grenade, friends buried beneath the
rubble in Sarajevo, his family's home and business burned down.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers how he, his 6-year-old sister and mother fled to
Austria with just the clothes on their backs; how he took care of
his sister, Irena, while his mother worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what was going on, but it was hard to understand why it
was happening,'' Gavranovic said. ``Everybody living there was
afraid of getting killed. You're scared. You can't sleep. You can't
eat. It's just a very bad feeling. I wouldn't want anybody to have
to experience it.''
</P>
<P>
   The memories were made fresher by the recent attacks in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can bring up post-traumatic stress,'' said Beardsley, who
is a psychotherapist in Phoenix. ``He's got some gruesome stories.
I don't push him on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gavranovic shares the past with those close to him. But he
mostly likes to forget and look forward to a life in America past
high school. He is like most other 17-year-old boys. He loves
basketball, cars, girls and going to the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody would guess from his command of English that he has been
in America only two years, or from his happy-go-lucky attitude and
quiet charm that he has an uncertain future here.
</P>
<P>
   Gavranovic is here on a student visa. In February, he turns 18.
After graduating, he could be called back to join the Croatian
army, if he is not going to school. It is not a world he wants to
be part of.
</P>
<P>
   Beardsley and her husband, Richard Smith, a federal attorney,
want to adopt Gavranovic and see that he obtains citizenship. They
are working with attorneys to push it through the system, which can
be slow.
</P>
<P>
   They are waiting for his mother, Danica, who lives in Vienna and
doesn't speak English, to give her consent. He can be adopted up to
age 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hurt her,'' Beardsley said. ``She lost her
husband and this is her only son, so she worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mother has said to him, `You're old enough now. You know
what is best.' ''
</P>
<P>
   What Gavranovic prays for is a college scholarship. He is making
high Bs, after learning English so well from his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a pretty good guy, but it's taken me a year to learn to
pronounce his name,'' said Knights teammate Michael Stidham.
</P>
<P>
   Gavranovic speaks four languages: Croatian, English, German and
some French. He is 6 feet 5 and a solid if not powerful forward for
the seventh-ranked Knights, scoring 10 points and grabbing seven
rebounds a game.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Z' has gotten more aggressive and physical,'' St. Mary's
Coach David Lopez said. ``I don't think he was used to the physical
play of American ball. He's gotten a lot better.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's coachable, nice, fits in with everyone around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gavranovic doesn't stay awake nights dreaming of an NBA future.
He just wants to stay here. He'd like to get an international
business degree.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Hall, a Phoenix resident and coach who saw Gavranovic at a
youth basketball camp near Vienna more than two years ago, calls
small four-year colleges across the country. He searches for a
coach as sympathetic as he was to Gavranovic's story, hoping
somebody will give the young man a scholarship. As long as he is in
school, he doesn't have to go back to Croatia, Beardsley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see myself going back there again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gavranovic is hoping to get a job after basketball season, but
that becomes tricky without citizenship and a green card.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, he may have to return to the uncertainty of Europe,
where his mother is struggling to keep her job. He doesn't have the
money to pay out-of-state college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has been a hurdle,'' said Hall, who hired Lopez at
Glendale Apollo in the late '70s and was responsible for getting
Gavranovic to St. Mary's.
</P>
<P>
   After spending his junior year at St. Mary's, Gavranovic
returned to Europe to renew his passport and be with his family. He
spent two months in Vienna, where an uncle gave his family refuge
six years ago. His uncle paid his tuition, roughly $4,000, at St.
Mary's last school year, but didn't have the money to for his
senior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was calling for some help and my phone rang,'' said Hall,
who travels the world to conduct basketball clinics. ``I picked it
up, and a person who wants to remain anonymous said, `My wife and I
talked it over, and we'll take care of (the tuition).' ''
</P>
<P>
   With the tuition taken care of, Smith and Beardsley opened their
home to Gavranovic just before the September deadline. He missed
the first week of school.
</P>
<P>
   Beardsley got to know Gavranovic last year, when he dated her
daughter, Vanessa. An extra room opened when Vanessa moved to
Hollywood to attend a performing arts school.
</P>
<P>
   Beardsley said she found Gavranovic to be perceptive, sensitive,
polite and well-mannered. She said he oftens asks if there are
chores he can do around the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband never had children, so he's like in heaven,''
Beardsley said. `` `Z' has said that if he had to choose somebody
other than his real father, it would be Richard.''
</P>
<P>
   Gavranovic keeps a framed picture of his father, Vojo, in his
bedroom. His father was 19 in the picture, the only photo remaining
of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember him,'' he said. ``We were close.''
</P>
<P>
   Gavranovic looks forward to another Christmas in America.
Beardsley's mother, who speaks German, will be here from
Connecticut, giving him someone to converse with in German. It also
will give him a greater sense of what he misses in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   His mother calls every Sunday and tells him to behave and keep
up his grades. He talks to his sister, a volleyball star at her
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family has been wonderful,'' Beardsley said. ``When he
first came here, they'd send boxes and boxes of gifts. They're very
happy that he's here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it is hard not seeing his mother and sister on
Christmas, Gavranovic is grateful for a gift that didn't come under
a tree. He is grateful for his American home, for a chance to
flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people around here have made me feel like part of
their family,'' he said. ``The coaches, the students, the parents.
They're great. It's been overwhelming. It feels like home.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
