<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-SMITH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UA'S SMITH CAN CELEBRATE RELATIONSHIP WITH FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keith Smith is home for Christmas with several gifts.
</P>
<P>
   There is Arizona's 11-1, Cinderella-like season. A No. 5
national ranking and a chance at a 12th victory Wednesday against
Nebraska in the Holiday Bowl are a couple of very nice stocking
stuffers.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more. A lot more.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's dad, Stu, is recovering from cancer and a series of
small strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Stu Smith's battle through radiation treatment and eventual
recovery coincided with his son's steady, poised role as one of
Arizona's quarterbacks. At Christmas, the father and the son can
celebrate a relationship that has been an inexhaustible gift for
both.
</P>
<P>
   One endured as the other emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my son really became a man this year,'' Stu Smith said
from the family home in Newbury Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The son will tell you that he has, in large part because his dad
was always there with advice on everything from throwing techniques
to the responsibility of sharing the quarterback role with Ortege
Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk two or three times a week and always before a game,''
said Smith, a junior who went home Thursday night during a break in
the Wildcats' workout schedule at San Diego State before next
week's game at Qualcomm Stadium. ``It's important to me. He'd just
give me advice like staying within myself. That sort of thing. My
dad and I have been communicating like that for as long as I can
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   They exchanged letters when Smith played in junior high school
and later as a prep star in the Los Angeles area. The communication
continued long distance when Smith went to Arizona. But, at times,
it was difficult this season.
</P>
<P>
   Stu Smith was struck with prostate cancer in June. He already
had suffered a couple of small strokes. Then, there was a third. At
the time, Keith was already in Tucson preparing himself for a
preseason camp at Cochise College and then the season itself.
</P>
<P>
   Then, questions swirled about his ability to share the
quarterbacking duties with Jenkins. In retrospect, those questions
had to seem minor.
</P>
<P>
   He always had relied heavily on his dad. He went to him when he
thought about transferring last spring amid speculation that
Jenkins would be the Wildcats' quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted me to stick it out, all along,'' said Smith, who
also had long talks with Arizona Coach Dick Tomey about his
options. ``He just wanted to make sure that I was convinced I was
doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was his dad who talked him into returning to college football
after a season in the Detroit Tigers' minor-league system. The
return meant Smith had to give back a $220,000 bonus, which is a
lot of money for a 19-year-old kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always told me to play the sport I want, not because of
money, but because of a love for it,'' said Keith, who at 5 feet 11
has always been written off by scouts and recruiters as too short.
``He used to tell me that when I was real young. Truth is, I didn't
really have to talk to him about returning that money. I did, of
course. But, all along, I knew I was going to give it back, because
of what he had taught me long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I'm playing football today, thank God. There's no
way I would be the football player I am without him. He made me
dedicate myself to the game and always reminded me that love of the
game was more important than the money or the politics that went
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   From the strict, sterile perspective of medicine and science,
it's impossible to say whether the son's leading role in Arizona's
season had any impact on his dad's recovery.
</P>
<P>
   But from the dad's perspective, there's no doubt his well-being
was propelled by the weekly news that, once again, his son's poise
and maturity more than made up for his lack of height.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' said Stu Smith, a track star at Los Angeles
Dorsey High nearly 50 years ago who also worked briefly as a
sportswriter for the old`` Los'' ``Angeles Herald-Examiner.'' ``I
went through the radiation for seven-and-a-half weeks through most
of the season. Because of that I wasn't able to go to all of the
games. I still went to as many as I could. But I was able to follow
the games, and that's been a real blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   The pride that the dad had for his son week after week proved to
be an immeasurable, yet powerful medicine, said Renate Smith, Stu's
wife and Keith's mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most definitely,'' said Renate, who believes the joy her
husband felt in his son's consistent play was a key addition to the
withering regimen of chemotherapy and medication.
</P>
<P>
   In a striking coincidence, one of Stu Smith's toughest times
happened on the same day that Arizona suffered its lone loss. Smith
wasn't able to watch the UCLA game on Oct. 10. The chemo sapped his
strength, knocked him down, as UCLA beat the Wildcats, 52-28, at
Arizona Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about it, because it came right in the middle of
radiation treatment when he was really feeling bad,'' Renate said.
</P>
<P>
   But there also was a moment the week before that provided a
great boost. Arizona was playing Washington at Seattle's Husky
Stadium. It was a night that Jenkins somersaulted into the end zone
for a game-winning touchdown that in many ways sums up Arizona's
improbable season.
</P>
<P>
   In a play that has been all but forgotten, a Smith pass was
pivotal in the drive that ended with Jenkins' bit of high-flying
artistry. Smith came on and tossed a first-down strike to Jenkins,
of all people.
</P>
<P>
   What Stu Smith remembers more than anything, however, is the
``Sports'' ``Illustrated'' photo of Jenkins in mid-vault. His
oldest son, Brian Smith, was at the game. Brian traveled to Seattle
because his dad could not. Brian got a seat behind the end zone
into which Jenkins landed, feet-first.
</P>
<P>
   In the background, the guy in the red coat with blue pockets is
Brian Smith. At one side of the photo, there's an exultant Keith
Smith leaping about three feet in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that and thought to myself: `How many dads can have both
of their sons in ``Sports Illustrated'' all at once?' '' Stu Smith
said. ``It was a reason to feel very, very good.''
</P>
<P>
   A reason to say Merry Christmas. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
