<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHARGERS-LEAF-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAF HAS LOST CHARGERS FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Finally, frustrated San Diego Chargers' fans are
buying into the decision to draft quarterback Ryan Leaf with the
second pick overall last April.
</P>
<P>
   He's a steal at half price, which is what Leaf jerseys were sold
for at Qualcomm Stadium last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Allan, manager of The Sports Fan sporting goods store,
wishes he would have thought of that. He can't give away Leaf's No.
16 jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come in and joke around about how much they are,''
Allan said. ``They say, `Do you have any Ryan Leaf jerseys?' They
know we're not selling any of these. They're just making fun of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Few NFL players have turned off their town faster than ``Cryin''
Leaf. It's so bad, ``San Diego'' magazine recently talked to
public-relations types on how to improve Leaf's image. The headline
on the story was ``Saving No-so-Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a terrible year,'' Leaf said. ``I've had
terrible years before and always have been able to bounce back. I
have to turn it into something beneficial. It's only going to make
me stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee ``Hacksaw'' Hamilton, who hosts a radio sports-talk show on
XTRA in San Diego, thinks many Chargers fans already have given up
on Leaf, who has annoyed teammates, feuded with the media, been
accused of going on a drunken binge near the Washington State
campus and been forced to deny recent reports that he fell asleep
in team meetings, was late to others and gone through the motions
in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has lost his teammates, lost his community and lost
games,'' said Hamilton, who formerly worked at KTAR in Phoenix.
``That's about as nasty a combination as you can get. He can't
play, can't study and can't talk his way out of situations. In 16
weeks of the season, not one of his teammates has come to his
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, as the Chargers prepare for their season finale
against the Cardinals at Sun Devil Stadium, teammates finally have
decided to speak out against Leaf, who has committed 19 turnovers
and thrown just two touchdown passes and hasn't started since Nov.
8.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Kurt Gouveia told ``Sports Illustrated'' that Leaf
needs to grow up. ``You're in the pros now,'' he said. ``Stand up
and be accountable. Futures are at stake. This is not a place for
kids who've got a lot of money to joke around.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior Seau, the Chargers' superstar middle linebacker, took
several shots at Leaf on Wednesday, two days after anonymous
players said they didn't want Leaf to start against the Cardinals
because of a lack of commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this game, you have to perform,'' Seau said. ``You can have
all the marketing tools. You can be touted as a potential great
athlete in the NFL, but what it comes down to is gaining respect in
the clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Chargers interim coach June Jones acknowledged that the players'
feelings about Leaf affected his decision to start Craig Whelihan
ahead of Leaf on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf knows he has a lot of enemies in the Chargers' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think my teammates want me out there,'' he said. &QL; 
Could've been a Cardinal
</P>
<P>
   Many NFL experts thought the Cardinals made a mistake when they
traded the second pick overall in last April's draft to San Diego,
bypassing their chance to get Leaf, the 6-foot-5, 240-pound Pac-10
Offensive Player of the Year at Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   They chose to stick with second-year pro Jake Plummer, who
entered this season with only nine career starts.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Plummer is the NFL's second-richest player, and Leaf has
been called a $31.25 million mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was put in a tough situa tion,'' said Plummer, who shares
the same agent as Leaf, Leigh Steinberg. ``The whole thing about
getting drafted so soon and having to play immediately is unfair
for any quarterback. He's a tough guy. He'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Seau thinks Leaf would be much better off if he were more like
Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see someone go to a position and take that
position and blossom,'' Seau said. ``We need more Jake Plummers in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf didn't get off to a great start with Seau in training camp
when he balked at paying a $2,800 bill the veterans ran up at a
sushi bar.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter to Leaf that it was a camp tradition. He didn't
want to pay and tore up the bill. He complained about it but
eventually paid.
</P>
<P>
   He won the starting job in preseason and led the Chargers to
victories in their first two games. But he completed only 1 of 15
passes for 4 yards on Sept. 20 in Kansas City and then cursed a TV
cameraman in the locker room after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Posner of the ``San Diego Union-Tribune'' newspaper wrote
about the incident, prompting Leaf to go into another
obscenity-laced tirade the next day. Leaf also threw a ball at the
head of Posner at practice but missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of his problems are self-inflicted,'' Steinberg said.
``His reaction to his performance in Kansas City was extreme. His
interaction with the reporter was caught on tape and played ad
nauseum. So instead of a 20-second blow-up, it was played like the
Rodney King tape over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf's behavior became even more bizarre. After throwing four
interceptions in a loss to the New York Giants the next week, he
questioned whether he was good enough to play in the NFL and said,
``It kind of feels like someone ripped my heart out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   He began to play better after Coach Kevin Gilbride was fired and
his replacement, June Jones, simplified the offense. But then
during the bye week, he went to Pullman, Wash., and was alleged to
have been thrown out of two establishments for rowdy behavior and
accused of throwing beer on two students, spitting on the outside
window of one place and telling numerous people, ``I can buy you
all.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't help his image in San Diego any when he said he had no
regrets about the Pullman incident and acknowledged that ``I'm not
very likeable'' and ``am simply paying the price for my fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Chargers General Manager Bobby Beathard was so upset with Leaf's
behavior, he said Leaf's ``career could be crumbling'' if he didn't
mature.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf has started only one other game and lost the San Diego
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bad Jim McMahon act,'' Hamilton said. ``It's all
staged and has all blown up in his face. He has to shut his mouth
and do things on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect that to happen this season.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Jones said he plans to use him against the
Cardinals, Leaf thinks he has played his last game of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to take Craig (Whelihan) out and ruin the
camaraderie,'' Leaf said.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't think his teammates have judged him fairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things have happened, people have pointed fingers,'' he
said. ``Sure I deserve some of the finger-pointing, but I've always
been told that if you're pointing the finger, somebody has three
fingers pointing back at you.''
</P>
<P>
   So he hasn't fallen asleep at team meetings?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how anybody would know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude won't sell any more jerseys. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
