<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS RECEIVE BLACKOUT EXTENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The NFL on Thursday granted a request by
Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill to extend the local-television
blackout deadline until 4 p.m. on Saturday for Sunday's season
finale with San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   League rules stipulate that a game must be sold out 72 hours in
advance, which would have been at 2:15 p.m. Thursday, to lift the
TV blackout.
</P>
<P>
   At the 72-hour audit, the club had sold 63,039 tickets in
72,994-seat Sun Devil Stadium, powered by unprecedented ticket
demand every day this week.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals (8-7) beat the Chargers (5-10), the Cardinals
would end the league's longest drought at 16 years and move on to
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill said he began talks with the league regarding the
blackout-lift extension on Tuesday. The NFL granted the request
because of the consistent ticket demand this week and the holiday.
The league has made exceptions in the past for teams approaching
sellouts during holidays or when unusual weather might have
prevented travel to a ticket office. It is the first exception
granted to his team, according to Bidwill.
</P>
<P>
   If the game is sold out by 4 p.m. Saturday, it will be telecast
live Sunday on KPHO (Channel 5).
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been probably the most dramatic response we've ever
had to a game in my memory,'' Bidwill said. ``If it had been a
normal week on sales I wouldn't have made the call. But we
experienced an unusual amount of business after the New Orleans
game last Sunday at the stadium and Monday was as large a day as
we've ever had in one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been building a hard corps of fans, we just extended
that last Sunday (in a 19-17 last-second comeback win over New
Orleans). A lot of people missed a great football game, and we've
had a lot of those in the last two years. It seems a lot of them
are thinking this might be one they don't want to miss.''
</P>
<P>
   The ticket office at the team's headquarters, at Warner and
Hardy in Tempe, will be open today from noon to 8:30 p.m., and
Saturday from 8:30 a.m. to 8:30 p.m. Tickets may be purchased at
ETM kiosks at Safeway stores on Saturday. The kiosks are closed
today. Telephone orders may be placed 24 hours a day during the
holidays at 1-888-ETM-TIXS.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are aware of at least two local businesses that
have purchased large blocks. Skip Sorely of Top Flight Construction
bought 100 to give to kids and Ron Clark of Ben Franklin Press
bought 100 as gifts for employees.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill said the club would not buy any remaining tickets before
the new blackout deadline because ``the blackout rule as a
precedent has been very important to the home gate.'' He said he
was aware of some talk that others would.
</P>
<P>
   John Smith, director of operations at Channel 5, was not
available for comment whether the station would guarantee the
sellout.
</P>
<P>
   The players are aware of the increased ticket demand and
interest in their fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to us,'' said tackle Lomas Brown, an offensive
co-captain. ``The crowd last week was great, but a sellout this
week would be terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill, whose team has suffered more than its share of hardship
and ridicule _ it hasn't had a winning record since moving here in
1988 _ acknowledged that he is surprised and moved by the
outpouring of support this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will sell out by game time but I don't know if it
will lift by Saturday. The league was very gracious to extend the
deadline to see if we can get the lift.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
