r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-TKACHUK-A     12-25 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-TKACHUK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK GETS GOOD NEWS  
 MINOR KNEE INJURY WON'T KEEP HIM SIDELINED LONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes received some good news on Thursday when
tests revealed Keith Tkachuk does not have any serious damage to
his injured right knee and that the left wing could be back in the
lineup early next week.
</P>
<P>
   A magnetic resonance imaging examination showed Tkachuk, the
team's leading goal scorer with 17, suffered only a sprained medial
collateral ligament, not a tear or any cartilage damage, as was
feared after he was checked hard into the boards during Tuesday's
6-2 victory in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's good news,'' Tkachuk said. ``I mean, I'm happy
it's not worse, but I'm not happy about having to miss any games,
period. But I thought it was going to be a lot worse than this. I
really did.''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Bobby Smith said Tkachuk had a slim chance of
being able to play Saturday night in Los Angeles, but he then
backtracked and said it was more likely that the power forward
would return Monday when the Kings visit America West Arena, or
possibly Wednesday when Wayne Gretzky and the New York Rangers make
their only trip to the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shooting for one of those two _ if I can,'' said Tkachuk,
who within the next several days is expected to be named to his
third straight All-Star Game. ``I'm still a little surprised, to
tell you the truth. I thought it was a tear. I had a real bad
feeling it was going to be a lot, lot worse than it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Wings forward Kris Draper crashed into Tkachuk in the first
period of Tuesday's game and then rolled over Tkachuk's knee, which
slammed hard to the ice. He continued to play, and later scored a
goal and added an assist as Phoenix beat Detroit for the second
straight time, but the knee stiffened up on him later that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really got a lot worse after that,'' he said. ``It was
really sore. But, hey, it turns out it isn't so bad. Our trainer,
Gord Hart, told me it won't keep me out very long at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, fellow left wing Mike Sullivan is also expected to
make a quick recovery from a broken big toe, suffered last week in
St. Louis when he got hit by a slap shot from Al MacInnis. Smith
said Sullivan could play Saturday, ``if he can get his foot into
his skate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have been fortunate all season when it comes to
injuries. They have lost just 35 man-games to injury through 29
games, among the fewest in the NHL after the first third of the
season, compared to 124 man-games lost at this point last season,
when they led the league with 475.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely important for every team to keep your players
healthy,'' Smith said. ``We've been very lucky this year. We've had
some injuries, but certainly, nothing serious, and that's obviously
been a big contributor to our success so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk, who recently also has been hobbled by a pulled groin,
has only missed three games to date despite playing a rugged style
and taking repeated abuse in front of the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a very durable guy his whole career,'' Smith said.
``He's a guy we don't expect to miss a lot of games. But when a
player hurts his knee, and there's some uncertainty there, and he's
still able to come back after a few days, yeah, you feel lucky.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
