<HEADER>
A6504 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FANTASY-MULLLER-A     12-25 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FANTASY-MULLLER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACKERS GAME KEY TO PLAYING TIME FOR 49ERS YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - This fantasy football season has been the tale of
three quarterbacks _  &UR; Randall Cunningham, Steve Young and  &UR; Brett
Favre.
</P>
<P>
   Why should the last week be any different?
</P>
<P>
   In many leagues, owners who drafted those guys probably went
deep into the playoffs. But for leagues that play the championship
game in Week 17, two of three may let you down.
</P>
<P>
   It shakes out like this: Favre will play, since the Packers must
beat the Bears to have a shot at hosting a wild-card playoff game
against the 49ers. If Green Bay wins their game, which begins at 11
a.m., that will force  &UR; Steve Young and his ailing knee into an
afternoon game against the Rams. A win would allow the 49ers to
host the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   But say the Packers lose. Improbable, but not impossible. With
nothing to play for, it's unlikely the 49ers will want to risk
losing Young for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Cunningham, who is nursing a broken left hand.
That's not the one he throws with, but Minnesota has home field
locked up throughout the playoffs. I bet we'll get a heavy dose of
 &UR; Brad Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I keep harping. Have the Fantasy Bowl in Week 16.
Saves on Bromo. Anyway, let's hand out the regular season Mully
Awards. &QL; 
Quarterback &QL; 
Most outstanding performer: Cunningham, Vikings. With more than
3,400 passing yards and 32 touchdowns, only Young has better
statistics. But in most fantasy leagues, Cunningham was drafted
much later that Young, if at all. That greatly increases his value.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest surprise:  &UR; Peyton Manning, Colts. I guess he is his
daddy, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest bust:  &UR; Scott Mitchell, Lions. He has some of the best
receivers around, and still gets benched for a rookie. &QL; 
Running back &QL; 
Most outstanding performer:  &UR; Terrell Davis, Broncos. That stampede
you heard is every defensive coordinator in the league rushing to
get the tape of Monday night's Denver-Miami game. The Dolphins held
Davis to 29 yards rushing, but he still has a crack at 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest surprise:  &UR; Jamal Anderson, Falcons. I knew he was in for
a good season, especially when his competition,  &UR; Byron Hanspard,
went down in training camp. But nobody thought Anderson would break
the Falcons rushing record and score 15 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest bust:  &UR; Jerome Bettis, Steelers. Three touchdowns. Three?
Something stinks in Pittsburgh. But  &UR; Bill Cowher must be a great
coach. After all, he has a jutting chin. &QL; 
Wide receiver
</P>
<P>
   Most outstanding performer:  &UR; Randy Moss, Vikings. He's already
amassed 1,300 yards and an amazing 16 touchdowns. Defensive backs
might want to try tying his shoelaces together or something. For
some reason, nobody's talking about his past anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest surprise:  &UR; Eric Moulds, Bills. The best thing that ever
happened to this guy was the arrival of  &UR; Doug Flutie, who isn't shy
about chucking the pigskin. The result: 1,278 yards and eight
touchdowns for the fleet-footed Moulds.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest bust:  &UR; Michael Irvin, Cowboys. Irvin has a 1,000-yard
season. But he's scored just one touchdown all year. &QL; 
Tip of the week
</P>
<P>
   Despite my earlier concerns, I'd go ahead and start Young.
There's no reason the Packers shouldn't clobber the Bears, and
Young is pretty tough. My guess is he'll play until 49ers get
comfortably ahead. &QL; 
Waiver wire &QL; 
Kind of late to rescue your squad, but a few guys might help.
Chicago overnight sensation  &UR; James Allen might be worth a try at
running back. And with Dallas playing a meaningless game against
Washington, you might want to grab Cowboys backup  &UR; Sherman
Williams, as Emmitt Smith gets some rest. &QL; 
One-hit wonder &QL; 
This week it's Miami wide receiver  &UR; Lamar Thomas, who scored three
touchdowns against the Broncos Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   And by the way, Merry Christmas! &QL; 
Bill Muller can be reached at 602-444-8178 or at
bill.muller(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
