<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Dec. 26:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BELARUS (Moscow) _ Russia's President Boris Yeltsin and
his Belarussian counterpart, Alexander Lukashenko, sign an
agreement to fuse the two Slavic neighbors into a union next year,
though with lots of caveats. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FIGHTING (Dateline to kum, Yugoslavia) _ Reports of fresh
fighting in the rebellious province. By Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-OUTLOOK (Solo, Indonesia) _ Seven months after student
demonstrations toppled the country's longtime ruler, Indonesia
remains in precarious shape, with its economy in a shambles,
political reforms stalled, and the student movement unappeased. A
Special Report by Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   BALLOON (Undated) _ Three balloonists abandon their bid to
become the first to complete a nonstop balloon trip around the
world after hitting dangerous weather in the Pacific Ocean near
Hawaii. By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-CHRISTMAS (Baghdad) _ Christmas in Baghdad. By Stephen
Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-PROSECUTORS (Washington) _ The Republican congressmen
appointed as managers of President Clinton's impeachment trial in
the Senate have as many questions as answers about the historic
roles they are set to play. By Frank J. Bruni. (1450 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RULES (Undated) _ Text of the 25 rules for impeachment
proceedings adopted by the Senate on March 2, 1868, to govern the
trial of President Andrew Johnston. (3000 words)
</P>
