   &UR; Other Washington &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-CHRISTMAS (Washington) _ Some government employees, like
firefighters for the nation, remain on station this Christmas day.
By Irvin Molotsky. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LA-CHRISTMAS-DINNER (Los Angeles) _ The Laugh Factory is serving
Christmas dinner to the down-and-out, as it has for 19 years. But
in L.A., a city where everybody is from somewhere else, it's not
just the elderly poor and homeless who come to the table. Here, you
find 20- and 30-something wanna-be stars who came to the city to
get famous, but today settle for getting fed. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL-LAW-SCHOOLS (Washington) _ In ``A Civil Action,'' which
opened Christmas Day, John Travolta plays plaintiffs' lawyer Jan
Schlichtmann as a bold and flawed man. But at law schools across
the country Schlichtmann is already a star, foibles and all, thanks
to Jonathan Harr's best-seller, which has become required reading
in courses in at least 50 law schools. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-BUS-ACCIDENT (Sayreville, N.J.) _ Developments in Thursday's
bus accident which killed eight passengers. By David M. Halbfinger.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as needed.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-OTTERS (San Francisco) _ Southern sea otters, the playful
darlings of the central California coast, appear to be diminishing
in number at a rate that perplexes and worries scientists.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-BURN (Orlando, Fla.) _ Faced with more long-range drought
conditions in Florida, state officials are seeking $35 million for
an aggressive controlled-burning program to prevent a repetition of
last summer's fires, which destroyed more than 500,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHEAP-CIGARS (Tampa, Fla.) _ America's infatuation with
expensive cigars appears to have already peaked. But one thing it
will leave in its trail is a revival of the cheap-cigar business.
By Jim Carrier. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Many Americans have discovered a new
way to keep family ties intact even during the hectic holidays:
huddled around Christmas trees in the lobbies of distant hotels, or
on cruise ships sailing the Caribbean. To be sure, the bright
lights and holiday decorations of New York and other big cities
have for decades attracted scads of vacationers at Christmas, and
many families have long celebrated the Christmas holidays on ski
trails or at the beach, especially families with lots of money and
time. Now, though, a broader number of Americans are going on
vacation at Christmas, not to be alone but to be able to spend time
with older children, parents or grandparents. By Edwin McDowell.
(1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-ON-TAPE (Undated) _ The growing popularity of audio books
has created cottage industries catering to one common trait: many
customers would rather rent than buy the long, expensive unabridged
recordings. In large part, that stems from a simple fact: The
number of times it is enjoyable to listen to a recorded book is
usually no more than one. By Michael Brick. (950 words)
</P>
