</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GATECH-HOFSTRA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ga. Tech opens ECAC play against Hofstra
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Georgia Tech is hoping to flex its newly discovered
muscles over the next two days in the Kodak ECAC Holiday Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets, who open against Hofstra today, are still
celebrating a 66-64 upset over No. 7 North Carolina earlier in the
week, three days after a humiliating 80-39 loss to No. 3 Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Tech played a solid game against the Tar Heels, commiting only
eight turnovers and shooting 44.6 percent. The Jackets won without
scoring a basket in the final 7:57, but they had managed to build a
62-50 lead before the drought.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra, which plays in the America East Conference, has a 5-4
record, but has been beaten soundly in games against two ranked
opponents, 89-59 to Maryland and 70-49 to St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackets play the Flying Dutchmen at 1 p.m. today and, if
they win, play Sunday at 2:30 p.m. against the winner of the
Iona-Pennsylvania game. With a home date against Mount St. Mary's
on Dec. 30, Tech hopes to enter its ACC schedule with an 11-2 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Tech's success depends in large part on freshman point guard
Tony Akins. Akins played poorly against Kentucky but performed much
better in the North Carolina game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony played a very smart game against North Carolina,''
Cremins said. ``Against Kentucky, he tried to do too much himself;
against North Carolina he was a team player. If you're a scoring
point guard, the one thing you have to learn is to become a pure
point guard, and Tony is going to learn to do that. When he passes
a lot, he feels like he's not going to get his offense, but all of
a sudden the offense comes to him. He looked like a different
player against North Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech also has the services of small forward Jon Babul, who had
missed four games and 19 practice sessions with a severe ankle
sprain. Babul gives Tech the tough defender it needs and is the
scrappy player who goes after loose balls and scores off of his
teammates' misses.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Collier, the Jackets' 7-1 power forward, sprained his
right ankle in the North Carolina game, but he said he plans to be
in the starting lineup today.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the upset of North Carolina, Cremins knows his team
isn't where it needs to be, but he has seen improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The win over North Carolina gives us something to build on,''
he said. ``We have a chance now and we've got to take it to the
next level. This team has got to approach every game as if it might
mean getting an NCAA invitation. We aren't good enough to take
anybody for granted, and we're not going to. We've got to go up to
New York and play in front of a lot of people in a big arena and
take care of business.''
</P>
<P>
   SCOUTING REPORT:
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA TECH VS. HOFSTRA
</P>
<P>
   When; where: 1 p.m. today; Madison Square Garden, ECAC Holiday
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   TV; radio: Fox SportSouth; WGST-AM (640), WGST-FM (105.7).
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: Bobby Cremins is 334-206 in his 18th year at Tech,
434-276 overall; Jay Wright is 55-67 in his fifth year at Hofstra,
55-67 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Records: Georgia Tech is 8-2, 1-0 in the ACC; Hofstra is 5-4,
1-0 in the America East Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Series: Georgia Tech leads, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Last meeting: Georgia Tech won 58-47 on Dec. 26, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra update: The Flying Dutchmen haven't backed away from a
tough schedule in the early going, losing to Maryland 89-59 and to
St. John's 70-49. Four players average in double figures, led by
Norm Richardson's 12.5 points per game. But Hofstra has only one
player taller than 6-7. The Flying Dutchmen score 62.3 points per
game and have given up the exact same average.
</P>
<P>
   Starting lineups: Georgia Tech -- guards, Tony Akins (5-11, fr.)
and Jason Floyd (6-6, jr.); forwards, Jon Babul (6-7, so.) and
Jason Collier (7-1, jr.); center, Alvin Jones (7-0, so.); Hofstra
-- guards, Jason Hernandez (6-0, jr.) and Craig Claxton (5-10,
jr.); forwards, Roberto Gittens (6-6, so.) and Norman Richardson
(6-5, so.); center, Duane Posey (6-7, sr.).
</P>
<P>
   Injuries: Georgia Tech -- Jason Collier (ankle) is probable;
Hofstra -- None is reported.
</P>
<P>
   -- Compiled by Norman Arey
</P>
