<SLUG> BC-FBC-HERITAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HERITAGE BOWL ADVANCE
 &HT;    Jaguars, 'Cats depend on 1st-year QBs
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bethune-Cookman College players insist that head coach Alvin
Wyatt is part preacher, part philosopher, part father and whole
``motivator.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We really believe in him,'' Wildcats senior wide receiver
James Adderley said. ``He gets us ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that readiness should be evident today, when
Bethune-Cookman faces Southern University in the McDonald's
Heritage Bowl at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors as Adderley and starting linebackers James Souder and
Anton Wright have a chance to win their ninth game of the season,
after winning only nine in the previous three.
</P>
<P>
   Southern will have a lot to say about it, however. The Jaguars,
who have played more games in the Georgia Dome than anybody except
the Atlanta Falcons, including regular-season appearances in the
Atlanta Classic, are 3-1 in Heritage Bowl games. They seem
confident in this showdown, billed as the ``Black College Super
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no place like home, and we feel like this is home,''
Southern senior defensive back Jackie Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt, in his second year as the Wildcats' head coach, scrapped
the pro-set passing offense and installed the triple option for the
'98 season. He will be banking on first-year quarterback Pa'Tel
Troutman to duplicate some of the exploits demonstrated during the
Wildcats' five-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a great athlete _ the player who makes us go,'' Wyatt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Troutman, at 5-feet-11, 175 pounds, has been clocked at 4.3
seconds in the 40-yard dash and was picked MEAC rookie of the year
after rushing for 1,054 yards and 15 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   His counterpart today _ Jaguars senior Sam George _ also is a
first-year starter.
</P>
<P>
   Since replacing two-year starter Marcus Jacoby, who quit the
team after the first game, George has averaged 193 yards passing a
game and hit on 51 percent of his 261 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   But Southern's primary ballcarrier, running back Steve Wofford,
a 5-10, 180-pound senior, said Heritage Bowl VIII might be
determined by someone other than a quarterback or running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come in here every year since I've been at Southern, and
we've made it happen in the Heritage Bowl twice,'' said Wofford,
who needs four rushing yards to reach 1,000. ``But in games like
this, with two evenly matched teams, special teams usually separate
the winner and loser. That's probably what it's going to come down
to (today).''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
