<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-VIPER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dodge Viper lures plenty of bites
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 CoxNews Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If nothing else, the Dodge Viper will go into the automotive
history books as a car that _ like the famed Carroll Shelby Cobra
sport cars to which it is related _ gave new meaning to the term
``snakebit.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, almost exactly 10 years after it was introduced as a
concept car at an auto show, the Viper is an outrageous,
street-legal creation that has sunk its fangs into considerable
worldwide respect as a true sports car. It's also credited with
helping a fading brand name re-emerge in the '90s by doubling its
sales in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   And the Viper has accomplished this despite being a
kidney-beating, ear-assaulting ride that has generally poor
visibility, can win a speeding ticket in most locales before it's
out of the second of its six gears and has a base price of $65,000
(comparable to the Braselton-assembled Panoz roadster).
</P>
<P>
   But Dodge execs knew they were on to something when the Viper's
introduction was followed by a barrage of orders even though the
car wasn't in production. The situation is much the same today,
with DaimlerChrysler limiting production to about 2,000 vehicles,
which keeps supply well behind demand and imparts the cachet
associated with Ferraris, Aston-Martins, Lamborghinis and other
exotic marques.
</P>
<P>
   The major difference is that the Viper, compared with those
six-figure cars, is a performance bargain, even a steal. It's
nowhere near as comfortable as Chevrolet's $30,000-and-up Corvette,
formerly the only world-class American sports car, but the Viper's
zero to 60 mph time of about four seconds and test-track top speed
of about 180 mph more than offset its harsh qualities.
</P>
<P>
   The test GTS coupe, with amenities that include power leather
seats, air conditioning, CD player and power mirrors, locks and
windows, showed why the Viper is a favorite of entertainers such as
Jay Leno and singer Dwight Yoakam. It's a fun ride with incredible
dry-weather handling, ultra-precise steering, brakes that will stop
on a hint of pressure and all that pure old American big-engine
power (460 horsepower and 500 pounds-feet of torque).
</P>
<P>
   The race-ready test Viper American Club Racing (ACR) version,
stripped of air conditioning, stereo and about 60 of its original
3,500 pounds, was also demonstrative in a Walter Mitty fashion. Its
engine and suspension are tweaked, but it remains street-legal,
while brutal enough to remind that its siblings won the '97 GT2
drivers' and manufacturers' world championships and its class this
year at LeMans.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder that the Viper's buff-magazine endorsements include
Automobile's claim that it's ``hard to knock'' and normally
conservative Consumer Guide's conclusion that ``few automobiles of
any price match its bold nature.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also difficult to call the Viper anything other than the
current ultimate expression of American automotive muscle and the
inspiration for bad fangs-for-the-memories puns.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicles: 1998/'99 Dodge Viper GTS coupe and Viper American
Club Racer coupe
</P>
<P>
   Prices as tested: $70,700 for GTS, $77,200 for ACR
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual air bags with switchable passenger's, dual
3-/5-point seat belts, heavy duty 13-inch power disc brakes
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrains: 8.0-liter V-10 engines (460 horsepower), six-speed
manual overdrive transmissions
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicles: 17-inch aluminum wheels on GTS coupe,
$500
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 12 mpg premium unleaded city, 21 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Leave the test driving to us. Make car buying easier with access
to Russ DeVault's auto reviews and other Wheels features through
the AJC's Stacks Information Service. Article reprints are $7 each.
Call 404-526-5668 or 1-800-756-4197.
</P>
<P>
