<P>
   Y2K _ WASHINGTON _ Think of it as a $600-billion fire drill. For
the next year, governments, businesses and citizens worldwide will
scramble to fix arcane computer code linked to arrival of the new
century. The Y2K millennium bug threatens to halt everything from
airplane flights to Social Security checks. But many segments of
the U.S. economy are in good shape. And Fortune 500 companies are
on their way to fixing Y2K computer glitches. Still, analysts
expect disruptions: Regional brown-outs, disruptions to business
supply chains, problems distributing federal payment through state
and county governments. And the estimated $600 billion to $1
trillion spent to fix the problem could cause a drag on world and
domestic economies. (Regan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-DATA _ A scorecard for industry segments' Y2K readiness.
(Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CONSUMERS _ WASHINGTON _ So what's a nervous Nellie to do?
The Y2K debacle has caused some Americans to play Chicken Little _
stockpiling food, brushing up on survival skills and getting ready
to hit never-used bomb shelters. But many analysts are urging
Americans to use common sense. Don't pull your money out the bank
and stick it under your mattress, but do have at least two weeks
cash on hand, fill up your gas tank, charge up the cellular phone
and have your heating oil tank filled. (Regan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CONSUMER-LIST _ A consumer checklist. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-LAWSUITS _ WASHINGTON _ If the technical problems aren't
hard enough, the folks who are trying to fix the gliche face the
potential of a flood of lawsuits. Lawyers are readying class-action
litigation against companies that could cost huge bucks. Some in
business see this as the next big reason to enact serious tort
reform. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: REPEATED Monday, Dec. 21 for all needing in (w) Washington
and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   An Atlanta illustration will be placed in the Business folder on
the Cox server.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-MONEY _ WASHINGTON _ Any candidate who wants to win
either major-party presidential nomination in 2000 will have to
raise $22 million to $25 million in 1999, leading campaign finance
experts tell us. That's more than $60,000 a day, 7 days a week. And
that's just the so-called ``hard'' money. Enforcement of federal
limits has become so haphazard that another expert says he can't
even guess at how much unregulated ``soft'' money will be raised
and spent. An explainer of why candidates must raise so much so
early, what the money is spent for, and which candidates are
favored in what pundits call ``the invisible primary.'' (Mollison,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With CAMPAIGN-DATA _ Top fund-raisers. For graphic or box.
</P>
