<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6628 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADS-SFCHRON-ADS &LR;      12-25 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL AD AGENCY FOCUSES ON IRONY TO SELL GOOD CAUSES  &HT;     BY CAROL EMERT
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - ADS   &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A close-up of dead fish lying cheek by jowl stares dully from
the BART station wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get stuck on the Bay Bridge and suddenly being trapped in an
elevator sounds like fun,'' reads the ad. ``Take BART on your night
out instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Hip and edgy aren't the first words that come to mind when
thinking of  &LR; BART, a bureaucratic agency that until recently ran
yesterday's news on its in-station monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's ads, though, are eye-catching and irreverent. They
have also helped boost off-peak ridership 15 percent in the three
years they've been running, said Gale Moses, BART marketing
projects manager.
</P>
<P>
   The BART ads are the work of Underground Advertising, a tiny San
Francisco agency whose client roster consists mainly of nonprofit
groups and other service organizations looking for support.
</P>
<P>
   But you won't find posters of doe-eyed children holding empty
rice bowls coming out of Underground's small office on Pier 9.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Walbridge and Chuck Cardillo, the agency's co-creative
directors, have replaced heart-tugging sentimentality, a mainstay
of public interest advertising, with irony _ a device more often
seen in commercial advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try never to pull a tear, although most of our issues are
heavy,'' said Walbridge. ``People's instinct is to turn the page if
they perceive something as being too negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Underground's five-person office created its first do-gooder ad
two years ago for the Environmental Protection Information Center,
a redwoods conservation group.
</P>
<P>
   The ad _ which featured the headline ``We're not trying to save
all the redwoods; 96 percent of them are already gone'' _ was ``the
most fun we'd had in five years,'' said Walbridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hang out in the woods on the weekend and then come
back and sell people crap that ruins the woods, there's just too
much of a disconnect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Walbridge and Cardillo have taken on mostly nonprofit
clients and other organizations, like BART, whose goals they
approve of. (Public transit cuts down on auto  &LR; air pollution.)
</P>
<P>
   Other clients include the Rainforest Action Network, Mother
Jones magazine and the Breast Cancer Fund as well as companies such
as Glencoe Foods, which makes healthful soups, and Parasound
Products, a stereo equipment maker. Underground's annual billings
reached about $3 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Walbridge and Cardillo's salaries are half as high as a few
years ago, when they mostly free-lanced for other agencies on large
corporate accounts such as Microsoft. But their work day is
incomparably more pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Most mornings Cardillo, who writes copy, and Walbridge, who
handles art, bike from their San Francisco homes to a coffee shop
(always an independent) where they brainstorm about creative
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Afternoons are spent in the office and evenings are spent at
home with their wives and children. Cardillo said he hasn't worn a
tie in a year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the two partners took off every other Friday, a
schedule their work load has not allowed this year. But they hope
to return to a similar routine in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important than the way they work is the satisfaction
of promoting causes instead of corporations, Underground executives
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, trying to sell shoes or sell booze seems really petty,''
said Lori Warren, Underground director of strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to have to rationalize what I was doing by saying `it's
moving the economy' or `it's helping my client,''' said Warren.
``Now we don't have to rationalize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Underground is trying to drum up business by convincing
traditional nonprofit advertisers that its edgy style works better.
Warren recently sent a pitch letter to Save the Children, a charity
whose ads for many years have featured sad-looking children and the
ever-earnest spokeswoman, Sally Struthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you see the same sappy ad over and over for 10 years you
become immune to it,'' said Warren. ``It probably works for
75-year-old grandparents, but not for this generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Underground's standard layout for issue-oriented ads also
borrows from commercial advertising. More than 50 percent of each
issue ad is devoted to images and the headline, while the problem
and recommended action are distilled into a few paragraphs of
smaller text.
</P>
<P>
   Ads that employ guilt-inducing headlines and are packed with
lengthy discussions assume that the reader cares as much about the
cause as the advertiser does, said Cardillo.
</P>
<P>
   Underground attempts to ``consider the point of view of the
target,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But an executive at San Francisco's other public interest ad
agency said it is a mistake to apply commercial strategies to
charitable ads. ``You're not selling widgets,'' said Herbert Chao
Gunther, president of the Public Media Center.
</P>
<P>
   Gunther said his organization recently completed an ad for Food
First that features a photo of ``a hungry-looking kid'' and
develops three points over  &LR; from more than 1,500 words of text. The
headline contrasts the number of millionaires in the United States
(3.5 million) with the number of hungry people (30 million).
</P>
<P>
   Unlike commercial advertising, ``You're really trying to reach a
few folks, you're not trying to reach everyone'' said Gunther,
whose agency bills about $25 million per year, mostly from the
Planned Parenthood Federation of America.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Kover, the editor of the Journal of Advertising Research,
said both approaches can work.
</P>
<P>
   Public Media Center's ad would appeal to people who are already
``deeply concerned and are looking for a way to channel their
interests,'' Kover said.
</P>
<P>
   Underground's ads, meanwhile, would ``grab (readers) and change
the behavior of people who aren't necessarily looking for this kind
of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Underground clients interviewed for this article said
Underground's ads met or exceeded their goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a big budget so it's important that we break
through the clutter,'' said BART's Moses. ``We must create very
noticeable advertising and I think Underground has done that in a
superb way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
