<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Dec. 27, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REHNQUIST-REVIEW (Washington) _ If there is a full-blown
Senate trial of President Clinton, Chief Justice William Rehnquist
will emerge from the hide-in-plain-sight existence of the Supreme
Court into the glare of the public spotlight. This raises the the
intriguing prospect of watching a man accustomed to being very much
in charge of a very controllable environment navigate in a realm
where normal expectations don't apply. By Linda Greenhouse. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SOUTH-REVIEW (Undated) _ The impeachments of Presidents
Andrew Johnson and Bill Clinton, 130 years apart, both show how
potent the North-South divide can be. With Johnson, it reflected
the aftermath of the Civil War. With Clinton, it comes at a time
when conservative Southerners hold virtually all of the Republican
leadership positions in Congress. Southerners have also been the
prime advocates of impeachment. By Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   ADULTERY-REVIEW (Undated) _ However it's defined, adultery and
its lies have generated a vast folklore of opinion and anecdote in
many cultures, an almost universal body of common law. A look at
some examples.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH-LANGUAGE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Millions of American students
still study French, despite the fading significance of France and
its language. French has ceded to English its longtime standing as
the first language of diplomacy. It has fewer speakers worldwide
than many other languages. So is French being taught out of
proportion to its role in the family of nations and the global
economy? By Jacques Steinber. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   SPEED-LIMITS-REVIEW (Washington) _ Almost every state has raised
its highway speed limit in what has become an unofficial test of
the long-held belief that speed kills. Three years into the test,
the answer is still unclear. By Matthew Wald.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moving in `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-BEGINNINGS-REVIEW (Johannesburg) _ Research indicates that
the AIDS virus came into existence in the 1940s or '50s in Africa.
If that's the case, what happened? Where did it go? How could the
virus, which now threatens to kill a quarter of Africa, have gone
virtually unnoticed for decades _ and then emerged in America,
decimating gays and hemophiliacs in the early '80s before starting
on a ruthless march around the world? By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   GERM-WARFARE-REVIEW (Undated) _ U.S. officials from President
Clinton on down are taking the threat of germ warfare very
seriously, with thousands of people and billions of dollars in
motion to address it. Is this prudence or paranoia? By William J.
Broad and Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S.-REVIEW (Undated) _ After the U.S. bombing of Iraq, the
stalemate continues. The U.S. has used one of the pillars of its
containment policy _ the threat of force _ but not used it
thoroughly. And the other pillars of U.S. policy toward Iraq are
now wobbling. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENTS-REVIEW (Beijing) _ China's recent crackdowns on
dissidents came at the end of a year when China's rigid political
system had seemed to be relaxing its grip, and dashed hopes that
China was poised for change. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Tim Hilchey (e-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
</P>
