<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981225.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EURO-BANKERS-2TAKES-N     12-25 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-BANKERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFOUND ECONOMIC CHANGES SEEN WITH ADVENT OF EURO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It has all the trappings of a gold rush: the lure of
riches, the frisson of risk, the headlong dash to stake the claims.
</P>
<P>
   The euro, Europe's single currency, makes its debut in just a
week, creating a vast currency zone from the Arctic Circle to the
Mediterranean. And to listen to the most optimistic of those
seeking profit there, the currency's birth will unlock a mother
lode of wealth that has set American investment banks competing to
export more of Wall Street's ways to Continental Europe.
</P>
<P>
   While these great expectations may be overblown, there is no
doubt that for investors and fund managers, the euro's arrival one
week from now will mean an unparalleled transformation. Trading in
11 separate currencies will disappear, creating a single financial
bloc with an economic output greater than that of the United
States. Many financial specialists forecast profound changes in the
way Continental European markets operate _ and increasing pressure
on Europeans to emulate the ways of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this wall of money waiting to come into the market,''
said Jeremy Isaacs, head of European equity business at the Lehman
Brothers office here. ``Do I think European investors are going to
become more like U.S. investors? The answer is: absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is not as if Continental European countries have
been slouches in positioning themselves for the coming euro zone:
Think only of megamergers like DaimlerChrysler, the Deutsche Bank
takeover of Bankers Trust or the pharmaceutical fusion of Hoechst
and Rhone-Poulenc.
</P>
<P>
   And the world's economic spiral and low growth forecasts for
Europe as a whole have muted some of the more bullish voices
forecasting a euro bonanza. ``I don't think you are going to have a
revolution,'' Isaacs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are going to have an evolution,'' he said. ``The question
is when, not if.''
</P>
<P>
   Euro coins and notes will not be introduced for two more years,
but all transactions between banks in the 11 participating
countries and all operations involving equities and bonds will be
denominated in euros starting next week. With only one currency in
play, European companies will increasingly be evaluated by equity
investors and fund managers across a broad field of competition
where pricing and performance are no longer disguised by national
currencies or local scales of importance.
</P>
<P>
   The euro zone ``redefines what is a blue chip,'' said David
Bowers, European equity strategist at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., arguing
that, for instance, a company regarded as a heavyweight in one of
the 11 countries would not necessarily make it into a euro index of
top companies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 11 separate government bond markets will be
replaced by a single euro debt market in which the divergent yields
of the past will be replaced by far more subtle calculations of
razor-thin spreads between, say, euro-denominated bonds issued by
Italy and euro bonds issued by Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-border acquisitions will be simplified by the euro, which
will eliminate currency risk within the zone because it will have
an immutable value against national currencies until they are
phased out altogether in the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies in the 11 euro countries alone have around
$1 trillion invested in their own governments' bonds, according to
Crispin Southgate, an analyst at Merrill Lynch. Pension funds have
a further $350 billion in the same bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Both those amounts are set to mushroom as fund managers look for
higher yields in the low-interest euro zone and strapped
governments place an ever-larger part of the burden for pension
provision on private citizens.
</P>
<P>
   These prospects have sharpened competition among the big
American investment banks that have their European headquarters
here and see themselves as best placed to deploy expertise won in
the United States. That has set alarm bells ringing for big
European institutions, which have been scrambling to acquire some
of the same skills _ and the same reach _ as the introduction of
the euro nears.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we have been seeing in the mergers in
European banking groups is European banks trying to get the
critical mass and the expertise to compete globally,'' said
Madeleine Hall, a European fund manager at Schroders.
</P>
<P>
   They have not always been successful. For all its size, the
giant UBS AG, born of Union Bank of Switzerland's merger with Swiss
Bank Corp., lost out badly in this year's meltdown of emerging and
speculative markets.
</P>
<P>
   Still, big European banks such as Paribas, Deutsche Bank,
ABN-Amro and Barclays are all hoping to translate strong local ties
and cultural affiliations into thriving business. ``These firms are
pretty powerful in their own markets,'' said Robert Morris, a
managing director at Barclay Capital. While American banks would
seek to expand corporate bond and other business in Europe, he
added, ``it doesn't mean to say that they are quickly going to
steal the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition is particularly fierce in the creation of new
indices for bonds denominated in euros _ a dry-sounding business
redolent of number-crunching that will still play a central role
both in the evaluation of fund managers' performance in a changing
market-place and, more gradually, in the way businesses raise money
to finance their operations.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, American financial institutions including
Morgan Stanley Capital International, Salomon Smith Barney, Lehman
Brothers, Merrill Lynch, Bear, Stearns and J.P. Morgan have devised
eurobond indices in anticipation of a new, performance driven
approach to investment in the 11 euro countries.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, only Barclays among the European banks has devised
a similar index, and that one is narrowly based on government bond
performance. In the last 18 months, the overall number of
benchmarks has risen to 14 from two _ a proliferation some bankers
view as excessive. Such has been the rush to new indices that 1998
has become known as the year of ``the battle of the benchmarks.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The institutions offering benchmarks are hoping not only for the
adoption of their indices as gauges for managers' and portfolios'
performance but also the business that comes with it. ``What
distinguishes one index provider from another is the reach of
services,'' said Richard Pagan of Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new euro indices are now heavily weighted toward
government bonds because corporate-bond issuance, though it has
grown rapidly over the last year, is still only a fraction of the
U.S. level.
</P>
<P>
   Government bonds in Lehman Brothers' U.S. aggregate bond index,
for example, take up 47 percent of the index while corporate debt
accounts for 21 percent. The same bank's euro bond index is
composed of 67 percent government and 12 percent corporate debt.
</P>
<P>
   According to Anant Patel, a managing director at Bear, Stearns,
the government bond market in the euro zone is currently worth some
2.25 trillion euros _ more than $2.6 trillion _ compared with a
corporate bond market now valued at some 690 billion euros, roughly
$800 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The expectation among fund managers is that those proportions
will change radically as Continental European banks re-examine
corporate loans and companies wean themselves away from reliance on
banks for financing.
</P>
<P>
   At present, said Merrill Lynch's Southgate, 90 percent of
corporate financing in Continental Europe is provided by bank
loans, compared with 50 percent in the United States. By some
estimates, fewer than 10 percent of Continental Europe's 1,700
investment-grade companies _ many of them in Germany _ have issued
public debt. That is set to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``European banks are looking more closely at how much money they
make,'' said David Munves, credit market strategist at Lehman
Brothers. ``Corporate loans are coming under scrutiny, due to
shareholder value in general.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major opportunity for new index providers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One indication of the likely shift toward corporate issuance is
the prospect of stepped-up activity by ratings agencies _ still an
unfamiliar concept to many European companies.
</P>
<P>
   Eric de Bodard, managing director for corporate finance in
Europe at Moody's Investor Services, said the number of European
companies to which Moody's ratings had been assigned grew by 100 to
more than 300 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the signs point to at least as active a year'' in 1999, he
said. ``Investors are going to be looking for more yield and are
going to diversify their portfolios without foreign exchange
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said Patel at Bear, Stearns, with the advent of a single
currency for financial transactions, the nature of portfolio
management will change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally in Europe, the way in which portfolio managers
have been able to deliver performance is to take views on relative
currency performance and the performance of spread relationships
between markets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival of the euro, though, ``the currency component
will disappear, which was one of the biggest components,'' while
interest rate spreads will shrivel. ``And now all of a sudden, you
ask the question: Where do I get value enhancement?''
</P>
<P>
   The result, he said, will be ``a very new investment dynamic for
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks see their indices playing into a European transformation
whose precise course is still unclear and may, indeed, face many
regulatory hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Many fund managers are hoping, for instance, that a boom in
private pensions will introduce vast new sums to the market, as
happened in Britain, whose pension fund industry is bigger than all
of Continental Europe's combined.
</P>
<P>
   Against that, Continental pensions are a ticking political time
bomb. Many Europeans regard a comfortable state pension as an
inalienable birthright and are uncomfortable with the notion of a
private pension provision familiar to an increasing number of
Americans. Moreover, European private pension funds, like European
mutual funds, face regulatory restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Russia's meltdown has dampened appetites for
corporate bonds, particularly high-yield bonds. That has made some
assessments more cautious. Corporate bonds, said Bowers at Merrill
Lynch, will provide ``one of the most exciting challenges that the
euro will bring about.'' But this year's financial problems, he
said, ``have left people a little nervous about rushing into
this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-98 1933EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981225.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6672 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUGS-SPORTS-ART-3TAK     12-25 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-SPORTS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUGS CAUSE MISTRUST AND CYNICISM TO PERMEATE INTERNATIONAL
SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Lyudmila Petrova of Russia developed a nosebleed during the
New York City Marathon in November, a television commentator
wondered, without evidence, whether Petrova had been using EPO, a
synthetic hormone used to increase oxygen-carrying capacity.
</P>
<P>
   When Mark Coogan, an American marathoner, notices athletes
starting to wear braces in their 20s, he wonders whether they are
trying to counter the misuse of human growth hormone, which can
increase jaw size.
</P>
<P>
   When Jon Brown, a star distance runner from Britain, sees
spectacular times achieved in track and field, his first reaction
is not amazement, but suspicion. ``I don't like to say it, but you
see someone run a great time and you say he's on drugs,'' said
Brown, the British record-holder in the 10,000-meter run. Drug
testing is so inadequate and distrust so rampant, he said,
``speculation is out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Doping scandals have become so commonplace in international
sports that fewer and fewer people trust either the athletes or the
officials charged with guarding against cheating. Many athletes,
coaches, administrators and scientists say that these sports have
become so disfigured by doubts, anger and fatalism over the
question of cheating through drug use that a widespread cynicism
about sport's basic integrity has taken hold. It is a skepticism
deepened by the fact that no tests even exist to detect some of the
most potent drugs that athletes are suspected of using.
</P>
<P>
   This year has produced an unprecedented spate of doping
scandals. The world's best cycling team was disqualified from the
Tour de France. Five Chinese swimmers were suspended from the world
championships. Michelle Smith de Bruin, the swimmer and three-time
Olympic gold medalist from Ireland, was banned for tampering with a
urine sample meant for drug testing. Track and field stars Randy
Barnes and Uta Pippig were punished for drug cheating. And the
president of the Italian Olympic Committee resigned under fire for
failure to police drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Together, these incidents have only contributed to a crisis of
confidence in international sports.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to say definitely how many of the world's top
athletes _ marathoners, swimmers, sprinters, cyclists, weight
lifters _ are using or have used drugs to improve their
performances. Olympic officials estimate the number at 10 percent,
while some veteran athletes put the figure at 30 percent or higher.
Among some athletes and others, there is the belief that the
problem is epidemic and that it is becoming increasingly difficult
to win without cheating.
</P>
<P>
   And so many people involved in international athletics say that
if the International Olympic Committee does not take decisive and
convincing action against drug cheating at a summit scheduled for
February, much may be jeopardized: spectator interest, the desire
of disillusioned athletes to continue competing, the continued
willingness of corporate sponsors to spend billions of dollars on
the Olympics and other sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, for many of those involved in world-class athletics,
the current environment _ big money is being chased by athletes
with easy access to drugs combined with a wholesale disregard for
the capability and competence of the officials trying to police the
problem _ has raised a disturbing question. If results cannot be
trusted, has a central tenet of sports _ that its records are
legitimate history _ been irreparably damaged?
</P>
<P>
   ``Something's got to change or the Olympics won't be what they
are,'' said Amy Van Dyken of the United States, who won four gold
medals at the Atlanta Olympics. ``There's going to be warfare at
the pool and the track. People are going to become completely
bitter about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Helmut Digel, the president of the German track and field
association, has gone so far as to propose wiping clean all world
records in the sport at the end of 1999 and starting over.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to bulldoze it and start new; it's not working,''
Anne Marie Lauck of the United States, who finished 10th in the
women's Olympic marathon in Atlanta, said of the current
drug-testing procedures.
</P>
<P>
   And so there exists a sense of grim urgency that the drug
problem be attacked now with the necessary resources or not be
attacked at all, said Dr. Don Catlin, who operates the Olympic
drug-testing lab at the University of California at Los Angeles and
is a member of the IOC's medical committee on doping. While he
remains optimistic, Catlin said, ``Sport as we now know it is
finished if nothing happens.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Worsening Situation: Tests Can't Keep Pace With Drugs
</P>
<P>
   While cheating in sports through drug use has been a problem for
decades, it has become clear to many in Olympic sports that things
have got profoundly worse. Advancements in the sophistication of
certain performance-enhancing drugs, as well as an increasing
brazenness and cleverness on the part of athletes inclined to use
them, has left honest athletes and official drug monitors
struggling to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous experts argue that the international effort to fight
drug use lacks comprehensive testing and uniform enforcement and is
short of research funding by tens of millions of dollars. This has
had the effect, athletes, coaches and drug experts say, of leaving
many athletes not only angry at each other, but also feeling
betrayed by those who are supposed to be policing their sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is difficult to win without cheating,'' said Arnold
Beckett, a British pharmacologist who was a member of the IOC's
medical commission for 25 years and who is now one of its harshest
critics. ``Anyone with a decent lab can use all the drugs they want
and never be caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-1990s, when no-notice, out-of-competition drug
testing began in earnest, most athletes were tested only during
competitions. Under those terms, according to athletes and
administrators, athletes learned to beat the system using
increasingly sophisticated gels, creams, patches and injections to
deliver drugs that were quickly flushed from the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the dumb get caught'' at competitions, said Dick Schultz,
executive director of the U.S. Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Unannounced testing, where athletes answer a knock at the door
and are subjected to a urine sample, is considered the only
effective way to catch cheaters in this age of high-tech drug use.
However, only 10 of the 34 international sports federations under
the Olympic umbrella conduct such testing, said Dr. Arne Ljungqvist
of Sweden, a member of the IOC's medical commission.
</P>
<P>
   Simply finding athletes for these tests can prove futile. If 150
athletes are chosen for random testing each month by the United
States Olympic Committee, about 50 cannot be found because of
address changes and other reasons, said Dr. Wade Exum, the head of
the USOC's doping program.
</P>
<P>
   But current testing, the experts say, suffers from an even more
elementary problem. Even when athletes are tested, scientists are
unable to tell synthetic versions of hormones from those that exist
naturally in the body. These include two substances that athletes
are suspected of using widely _ erythropoietin, or EPO, which is
used by athletes to increase oxygen-carrying capacity and was at
the center of the Tour de France scandal, and human growth hormone,
or hGH, which is used by athletes to increase explosive strength.
</P>
<P>
   Coogan, the American who finished 41st in the men's Olympic
marathon in Atlanta, said he was convinced that rampant EPO use had
factored significantly in the searing marathon times run in recent
years. From 1989 through 1993, there were 41 marathon performances
under 2 hours 10 minutes. As of early November, there were 52
sub-2:10 marathons this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you want to quit running,'' Coogan said.
</P>
<P>
   At minimum, Coogan and others said, the lack of adequate testing
for EPO and hGH produces a kind of destructive uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Such ambiguity can also prevent possibly innocent athletes from
effectively clearing their names of suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   The sprinter Florence Griffith Joyner, who won three gold medals
at the 1988 Summer Olympics and set world records that year at 100
and 200 meters, was widely suspected of using performance-enhancing
drugs because of the dramatic improvements in her times and her
muscularity. She was publicly accused by another athlete of using
hGH, but Griffith Joyner denied ever using banned substances, and
she never failed a drug test. Because no test exists for hGH,
however, the skepticism never went away.
</P>
<P>
   When she died in September of suffocation related to an
epileptic seizure, questions were renewed about the legitimacy of
her performances. A more comprehensive drug-testing system could
have caught her or cleared her name for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really sure that most athletes are clean, but there is no
scientific proof that they are clean,'' said Dr. Patrick Schamasch,
a French surgeon who is medical director of the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   In another troubling episode, the president of the Italian
Olympic Committee, Mario Pescante, resigned last September over
allegations that players in Italy's soccer league were rarely
tested for steroids and that positive tests were covered up and
documents were destroyed. Rome's drug-testing lab also was
suspended for three months by the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Sandro Donati, a researcher and former coach who heads the
scientific center of the Italian Olympic Committee, later charged
that in the mid-1980s, the Rome lab was used to make sure that
steroid levels of Italian track and field stars and weight lifters
were kept below punishable limits. He said that Primo Nebiolo, an
Italian who is now president of track and field's world governing
body, knew of the manipulation, which Nebiolo vehemently denied.
</P>
<P>
   Donati, who has been working with prosecutors and the police,
has estimated that as many as 700 doctors in Italy are aiding
athletes in their doping efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very, very bad history, but I am afraid in many
other countries the situation is similar,'' Donati said in an
interview. ``This is the history of modern sport. But this is not
sport. This is another thing, like gladiators.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the experts assert, some current drug tests have the
unintended effect of encouraging cheating.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in sports such as cycling and cross-country
skiing, athletes can be suspended if they have a hematocrit, or
percentage of red blood cells in whole blood, above 50 percent. But
since the average person has a hematocrit level of 38 to 42,
considerable boosting with a drug like EPO is possible with
impunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you set a speed limit of 50, everyone is going to rise to
49,'' Catlin said. ``That, to me, promotes doping.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, two elite German swimmers, Chris-Carol Bremer and
Mark Warnecke, said that the use of EPO and testosterone was
widespread in their sport and that doctors easily kept hormone
levels below limits considered to be cheating.
</P>
<P>
   A backlash of protest and denial followed, and a disappointed
Bremer, a bronze medalist at the 1994 world championships, told
German reporters: ``Nothing will change in my active career. This
will go on forever.''
</P>
<P>
   This thick sense of suspicion engulfed the U.S. track and field
championships last summer in New Orleans, where Jon Drummond, one
of the world's top 100-meter sprinters, strained a groin muscle
during a preliminary round of the 100 meters. Another sprinter at
the event, Jeff Laynes, made an oblique reference to doping,
telling Drummond, ``That's what you get for taking that stuff,''
and insinuating that Drummond had used drugs for an edge.
</P>
<P>
   Drummond, who has never failed a drug test and has been an
outspoken anti-drug advocate, confronted Laynes, told him the
unfounded remarks were destructive and even invited Laynes to live
with him to check on his training.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of stuff has got to stop,'' Drummond said. ``It's
killing our sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, though, he claims it has killed something essential
inside himself _ his desire to do his best. He thinks that the
faster he runs, the more people will suspect him of using
performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the back of my mind, there's the fear of breaking the world
record and everybody saying I'm dirty,'' Drummond said. ``I'm
afraid to be successful because I don't want to be considered a bad
person.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Flawed System: Wrong Athletes May Be Caught
</P>
<P>
   The full reach of the confusion and despair provoked by
widespread drug cheating, and the badly flawed policing of it, can
be appreciated in the person of Doriane Lambelet Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, once a world-class runner and now a lawyer, has lost
races to runners she thought benefited from drugs, most memorably
an 800-meter race in Munich 15 years ago when Jarmila Kratochvilova
of Czechoslovakia set a world record of 1 minute 53.28 seconds that
has not been approached since. Coleman has prosecuted cases against
athletes charged with drug use. And she has defended athletes she
thinks were falsely accused of drug use as a result of flawed
testing.
</P>
<P>
   So now, she says, she talks with her two young sons and wonders
whether she should discourage them from even trying to compete at
the top levels of international sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have despair on both sides,'' Coleman said. ``As an athlete,
there's so much cheating, you wonder why you're competing. On the
other side, the system to protect the innocent is devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Coleman, while able to produce no proof, said she used
to be told before races by officials that she would be selected for
``random'' tests afterward. She said she believed she was given the
unusual notification because officials knew she would pass the test
and thus avoid embarrassment for the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sacrificed me and the others who were clean, rendered
moot our work and our dreams, all for the greater glory of the
enterprise,'' said Coleman, who is now a professor of law at Duke
University.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said her lack of faith in the ability of international
sports organizations to fairly and effectively limit cheating had
not lessened in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the near certainty among athletes and sports officials
that large percentages of athletes are using performance-enhancing
drugs, only two athletes at the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta were
caught using something as serious as steroids. Further, the IOC has
allowed coaches implicated in drug scandals in East Germany to
coach in Australia and China without sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   And when athletes are caught, Coleman wonders whether they are
often the wrong athletes. The test to detect the use of
testosterone, the male sex hormone, as a steroid has encountered
strong challenges because of its imprecision. Female athletes such
as Pippig, the German marathoner, and the American star Mary Slaney
have contended that the test is not reliable for women because of
hormonal fluctuations caused by menstruation, birth control pills
and the drinking of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman represents Slaney, whose disputed drug test at the 1996
Olympic trials remains unresolved two years later. Track and
field's world governing body will not say exactly what substance it
believes Slaney took, Coleman said. Meanwhile, her reputation has
suffered, as has that of Dennis Mitchell, the three-time Olympic
sprint medalist who was suspended for a similarly suspicious test
last summer by track's world governing body, only to be cleared
this month by the American track and field federation.
</P>
<P>
   While Coleman said she wanted a strong drug-testing program, she
feared that a new rush to catch athletes might result in a sort of
athletic McCarthyism. She would not encourage her two young sons to
become Olympic athletes, Coleman said, because ``I don't want their
dreams crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   A Changing Landscape: Fuzziness on What Is Really Cheating
</P>
<P>
   The praise heaped on Mark McGwire for his 70-home run season,
despite his admission that he used a nutritional supplement banned
in many other sports, has created further disgruntlement and anger
among athletes in international sport who are struggling with the
increasingly thorny question of just what constitutes cheating.
</P>
<P>
   While McGwire has been hailed as a savior for baseball, Randy
Barnes, the 1996 Olympic shot put champion, faces a lifetime ban
for using the same supplement, androstenedione, known as andro.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' case has forced athletes and officials to examine the
blurred line along which performance enhancement becomes cheating.
Should an over-the-counter supplement like andro, legally available
to the public, be considered doping? A banana enhances performance
because it contains potassium, said Greg Duplantis, who is Barnes'
lawyer. Is eating a banana cheating? he asked. Or lifting weights?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Alice in Wonderland,'' said Duplantis, who was an
alternate on the 1996 Olympic team as a pole vaulter. ``Cheating is
what they say it is today. If baseball bans andro, is McGwire now a
cheater?''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's anti-doping conference in February will attempt to
establish an independent agency to direct a worldwide control
effort, a uniform drug policy for international sports and a
research fund to develop a more comprehensive testing program. The
White House has promised $1 million to aid in drug research, and
the IOC may augment that with $25 million from television rights
fees, although scientists believe a fund two to four times that
amount is needed if the drug police are to draw even with the
cheaters.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the cries for doping reform, a few voices for the
legalization of performance-enhancing drugs have made themselves
heard. The rationale for accepting doping is that the current
system is unworkable.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about what is fair and doable when it comes to drug
testing will only grow more complex for the next generation of
athletes. Officials with the IOC have already said that they are
struggling to confront the testing presented by a dangerous form of
synthetic blood they believe is being used by cyclists and
cross-country skiers. And ethicists and experts are wondering about
the future of sports in a world in which genetic engineering is
increasingly commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, certain experts suspect that the eventual acceptance of
doping may be inevitable because of disillusionment, the inability
to spend infinite dollars on the current system and the
increasingly sophisticated development and use of hormones.
</P>
<P>
   With widespread public use of such nutritional supplements as
androstenedione and creatine, and the therapeutic use of
testosterone to boost sex drive and prevent wasting in AIDS
patients, the punishment of athletes for using the same substances
will eventually come to be viewed as selective enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm predicting that within 10 or 20 years, they will have no
choice but to accept what I call soft doping,'' said John Hoberman,
a professor at the University of Texas and author of the book
``Mortal Engines: The Science of Performance and the Dehumanization
of Sport.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, that is not something the IOC is likely to
consider. And so frustration and ambivalence will most likely
prevail for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the guilty and innocent are presumed guilty,'' said Rich
Young, general counsel for the United States swimming federation.
``If you do something extraordinary, you're really guilty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
