<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (dw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LOAN LOSSES FOUND AT JAPAN'S 17 LARGEST BANKS
</P>
<P>
   Japan's 17 biggest banks had $427 billion in problem loans as of
March, 12 percent more than they had reported, a Government audit
has found. The Financial Supervisory Agency said it had found 49.5
trillion yen, or $427 billion, in problem loans, 5.4 trillion yen
more than the banks had calculated.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem uncovered in the audit was that some banks
applied more lenient write-off rules for loans to their financial
affiliates than to other borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN OIL OUTPUT STABLE
</P>
<P>
   Russian oil production fell 1 percent this year, less than
expected, as the ruble's plunge offset low world oil prices and
provided producers with cash to maintain output, a government
official said.
</P>
<P>
   NIKKEI CLOSES 91 POINTS HIGHER
</P>
<P>
   Japanese stocks closed higher for the first time this week as a
rise in government bonds lessened worries that bank profits would
shrink further. In Tokyo, the Nikkei average of 225 stocks rose
91.22 points, or seven-tenths of 1 percent, to 13,797.95. That left
the benchmark index 10 percent below its level of a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES EXPECT LOWER EARNING
</P>
<P>
   Several major airlines, including UAL Corp.'s United Airlines,
US Airways Group and Continental Airlines, are expected to report
lower earnings for the fourth quarter because of competition from
discount carriers, a reduction in corporate travel budgets and an
increase in the number of seats they had to fill.
</P>
<P>
   OIL INDUSTRY'S ANNUS HORRIBILIS
</P>
<P>
   The oil industry has unexpectedly suffering through a year that
some are calling a ``blood bath.'' Oil prices averaged $13.13 in
the fourth quarter, down 34 percent from a year earlier. The
biggest American oil companies are expected to report earnings
declines of between 32 percent and 90 percent for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   HITACHI SIGNALS STRATEGY SHIFT
</P>
<P>
   Hitachi Ltd., Japan's largest electronics manufacturer, may have
signaled an effort to speed up its decision-making process when it
appointed a new president, Etsuhiko Shoyama. Unlike many previous
presidents of Hitachi, Shoyama has worked extensively in
audiovisual products and in the company's information and media
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   GROWTH SLOWS AT REAL ESTATE TRUSTS
</P>
<P>
   The nation's real estate investment trusts are expected to
report that earnings growth slowed to about 11 percent in the
fourth quarter as slumping stock prices made it harder to finance
property acquisitions. The share prices of REITs have fallen this
year because of concern about a slowing economy and a rise in
construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
