A6692 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BETTER-RESUME-LADN     12-25 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTER-RESUME-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY BEN SULLIVAN 
</HEADLINE>
 
Honesty, clarity, brevity necessary to good resume 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Let's face it: We're all suckers for good
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   When faced with two or more products of comparable quality,
buyers are drawn to the one with the well-crafted advertisement,
while also-rans get passed over like so many bruised tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   A resume is your 30-second plug to a prospective employer. By
highlighting your experience, skills and talent, it identifies you
as someone who can do a job and do it well. It's not meant to be
the final word on who you are, but if successful, it will lead to
the next step in the job-search process, the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really your first introduction to a prospective employer
and the only thing they're going to see before talking to you _ if
they talk to you,'' said Joyce Underdown, owner of The Resume
Connection in Tarzana, which prepares resumes for job seekers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the truth is, there is no one correct way to write a
resume. Indeed, how and what you say will depend on the job you're
after. But a few common denominators exist for all successful
resumes: honesty, clarity and conciseness. No matter how impressive
your accomplishments, a muddled resume can be the kiss of death to
your prospects.
</P>
<P>
   1. Personal data _ Your name, complete address, telephone number
and e-mail address. It's hard to be creative with this, so don't
even try.
</P>
<P>
   2. Objective _ A one-sentence (keep it focused!) description of
the type of job you're after, tailored to the position you want.
Good: A senior management position in a public relations firm
serving Los Angeles' entertainment industry. Bad: A job that will
allow me to use my extensive management, writing and creative
skills in public relations and marketing, ideally serving Southern
California clients in the music and/or film business.
</P>
<P>
   3. Experience _ Here's where you can brag _ in an understated
way _ about how much tail you've kicked at past jobs. In reverse
chronological order, list your work history, providing the name of
the employer, the position you held, the dates, skills involved and
one or two of your significant accomplishments, such as landing a
big, new client or being singled out by the boss for your
outstanding work. If your job involved supervising others, be sure
to mention the head count.
</P>
<P>
   4. Education _ List your highest degree or certificate first,
the name of the school and dates you attended. If you went to
college, don't bother mentioning your high school. But if you hold
an advanced university degree such as a master's or Ph.D., list
that and your bachelor's degree and the schools that issued them.
</P>
<P>
   5. Related skills _ Include information on any foreign languages
you speak, computer skills (including programming languages and
specific software appropriate to the job), talents for
presentations or public speaking, and the like.
</P>
<P>
   6. References _ It doesn't hurt to include a list on a separate
sheet of paper of three people who know you in a professional
capacity. But you can also simply state that references are
available upon request.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
