<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FACE BIG TESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just in the nick of time, the Los Angeles Kings
are showing signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is whether they can keep it up.
</P>
<P>
   With a home-and-home series against the powerful Phoenix Coyotes
(19-6-4) _ at the Forum tonight and in Phoenix on Monday _ the
answer to this question will come quickly, an answer that may carry
with it any hopes the Kings (10-20-3) have of mounting a serious
playoff pursuit in the second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In their first two meetings this season with the Coyotes, both
at the Forum, the Kings were outscored 7-0. Tonight, however, the
Coyotes are expected to be without star left wing Keith Tkachuk,
who has a sprained right knee. (Coyotes general manager Bobby Smith
said Tkachuk has a slim chance of playing tonight.) Tkachuk may be
able to play against the Kings on Monday, however.
</P>
<P>
   In their first home game in nine days, the Kings will have a
distinctly different look from the team that blew a third-period
lead on Dec.17 in a 5-4 overtime loss to the New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, general manager Dave Taylor traded a 1999
second-round draft choice to Buffalo for the rights to 29-year-old
right wing Donald Audette. In two games as a King, both on the
road, Audette has scored two goals.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Kings have regained the services of captain
Rob Blake, who has recovered from the broken foot that sidelined
him for 15 games and outlasted the NHL suspension that forced him
to sit out three games, including that dismal loss to the
Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Kings needed to be reminded of Blake's value to
them, but his effect on their performance has never been more
graphic than this season.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Kings are 10 games below .500 this season, scoring
73 goals and allowing 91.
</P>
<P>
   Blake has appeared in 15 games. In those games, the Kings are
7-5-3, outscoring the opposition, 33-27. Without Blake in the
lineup, the Kings are 3-15 and have been outscored 64-40.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have allowed an average of 1.8 goals a game in Blake's
appearances and 3.56 in the games he's missed. Blake has appeared
in three of the Kings' past 21 games. The Kings have won just six
of their past 21 games, but in Blake's three appearances, the Kings
are 3-0 and have outscored opponents 10-1.
</P>
<P>
   As the Kings resume play following the NHL's two-day Christmas
hiatus, they have 23 points, the fewest of any of the 13 teams in
the Western Conference. They are seven points behind St. Louis and
Vancouver, the teams that hold the last two playoff berths.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Kings close that gap in their final 49 games? How they
fare in the two games with Phoenix should provide a strong
indication of whether they are capable of putting together the
streak that will be necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-98 2034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
