<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6734 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-BUSCRASH-VICTIMS-1     12-25 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-BUSCRASH-VICTIMS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: fancy craziness.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arkadiy Kagan, who immigrated to Brooklyn from Minsk five years
ago and covers the community for a Russian newspaper, said the
casinos in Atlantic City were a novelty to newcomers, to whom the
clang of the nickel slots sounded a lot like the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't available in the Soviet Union, you couldn't attend
casino,'' Kagan said. ``It's a fascination with freedom, with
wealth, which was prohibited in former Soviet Union. It's like
dream wealth. You are wealthy, you can spend money in casino. Even
if you spend $5 in 5-cent coins, it's like self-identification with
wealthy people.''
</P>
<P>
   With just 22 passengers, the bus Thursday was only half-filled,
perhaps because of the coming Christmas holiday. Most, like Murray
Hollander, were retired people who made small-change gambling a
hobby, faces familiar to one another from many trips south.
</P>
<P>
   Hollander, 72, has spent his entire life in Brooklyn. After his
open-heart surgery a quarter-century ago, he stopped working as an
accountant. Never married, siblings dead, Hollander goes to
Atlantic City as often as four times a week, as much to forget
about his gall bladder and prostate problems as in hopes of hitting
it big.
</P>
<P>
   Dice is his game. He plays enough to get complimentary rooms at
some of the casinos. Once, he won a couple thousand bucks. Then,
another time, he lost it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get away from the city,'' Hollander explained in a telephone
interview from his bed in the critical care unit of Memorial
Medical Center in South Amboy, N.J.. ``I'm all alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Hollander had some paperwork to do, and almost stayed
home. But he got bored rattling around in his apartment, so he went
to the corner store where he catches the bus and hopped on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my mind up not to even go yesterday, but like a jerk, I
said, let me get out of here,'' Hollander said. ``If a thing is
going to happen, it happens. You can't regret anything in life. You
might as well say you're not going to go out during the day. I'm
not afraid. I do things.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollander said he was sitting in his favorite seat, directly
behind the bus driver, watching a comedian on the video screen,
when the accident happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thrown, and all of a sudden I was in pain,'' said
Hollander, who was treated for severe chest trauma. ``I called for
help. I don't know who got me out. My mind was all confused. I
didn't know who I was or how I got there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he added, ``how I survived.''
</P>
<P>
   But survival itself is bittersweet. The tragedy tore apart four
couples: Rosa Avrutsky, Fred Lewis, Mrs. Tsatskina and Shirley
Weiss were among the dead; their spouses are on the injured list.
Vladimir Avrutsky and Matvey Tsatskin were called upon to identify
the bodies of their wives, a state police officer said.
</P>
<P>
   The other fatalities were Michael Grumet and Paul Ludy.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewises were photographers, a childless couple who moved
into the large red-brick co-op building a block from Mrs.
Hirschhorn about five years ago and built a darkroom inside. When
they ate in a restaurant, they brought leftovers home for their
neighbors; their extensive collection of Disney paraphernalia
delighted the children of their friends down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time my grandchildren came, they would give them a toy
or little animals,'' said Bernice Geller, who lives in the
apartment next door. ``They brought us things from Atlantic City _
key chains, candies, little things.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, as they began the arduous process of notifying next of
kin that stretched until 3:15 a.m. Friday, police knocked on Mrs.
Geller's door to tell her of the tragedy. Mrs. Geller let the
officers into the Lewis apartment, where they retrieved dozens of
messages off of the answering machine, so they would know which
friends to call. The phone had been ringing all day, Mrs. Geller
said, with people who knew the Lewises go to Atlantic City about
once a month, everyone wondering the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like glitter, like safe glitter,'' Mrs. Geller said to
explain the attraction of the place. ``You're safe there. Even an
older person or even a single person wasn't afraid to go there
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   For Minnie Hirschhorn, who walked with a cane and had an
apartment filled with her needlecrafts, Atlantic City was a
connection to her late husband, Sol, who taught her to play the
slots. In her widowhood, it filled the time when she wasn't sewing,
cooking, crocheting or reading the magazines that she generously
shared with the other elderly women who lived in her building. She
gave one neighbor the newspaper when she was finished; a family
down the hall got her coupon circulars.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Win a million, Minnie,' I'd always tell her. She said if she
won a million, I'd be the first to know,'' said a neighbor of Mrs.
Hirschhorn who declined to give her name. ``She really loved going
to Atlantic City. She died the way she lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Leidner teased her about her passion. ``What are you, an
addict?'' she asked. ``If I liked sex that doesn't mean I'd become
a hooker.''
</P>
<P>
   But the jibes were loving, friend to friend. Mrs. Hirschhorn
always told her neighbor when she was going out of town and checked
in when she got home, her telephone call usually coming around 9
o'clock as Mrs. Leidner dozed in front of the television.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the night before the trip, several neighbors begged
her to reconsider. ``Don't you hear the radio, about the snow?''
Mrs. Leidner recalled asking. ``You're flirting with death.'' On
Christmas Day, when the list of fatalities was tallied, she wept at
her own prescience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a witch,'' Mrs. Leidner said. ``It's a terrible
thing. What can I tell you?''
</P>
<P>
   Both Mrs. Hirschhorn and Hollander were especially partial to
the driver who was at the wheel for the deadly ride. Hollander said
that the driver, Russian-born Valentin Viner, always sped down the
Garden State Parkway, giving his passengers more time at the gaming
tables. Mrs. Hirschhorn told friends of his kindness in escorting
her safely into the lobby of her building at the end of the
journey. Once, with a different driver, she had tripped getting off
the bus and injured her foot.
</P>
<P>
   Lying in his hospital bed, Hollander wondered when he might be
back at the crap tables. He was never a high roller, but the
frequent trips to the Hilton and other hotels had earned him some
perquisites. For New Year's Eve, the casino had given him a
complimentary room, plus tickets to a show.
</P>
<P>
   He is not sure whether he will go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
