<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOLCHAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chat drives the internet
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before the Internet became the world's largest shopping
mall, chat _ live typed conversations in cyberspace _ was driving
its growth.
</P>
<P>
   It still is.
</P>
<P>
   America Online was launched by founder Steve Case with the idea
that people all over the world want to talk to each other, and he's
right. Next to e-mail, chat is still the most popular feature on
AOL. Members regularly chat about politics, books, romance and what
they had for dinner last night. Christmas Day was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jupiter Communications, teens are the largest group
of online chatters. Jupiter reports that more than 42 percent of
wired teens chat regularly, as do 26 per cent of online young
adults. Seniors spend the least time chatting online, with only 10
percent chatting regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers were spending the holiday in a variety of chat rooms
discussing everything from parents to rock music.
</P>
<P>
   The Entertainment Asylum Teen Chat was busy Christmas Day, with
teens typing in all the lyrics to Adam Sandler's Hanukkah song and
talking about what they got for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   In AOL's Electra Teen chat area (keyword Electra), an entire
area was devoted to helping teenage girls beat the holiday blues.
Electra's teen area encourages young women to draw pictures and
write stories and poetry to help express their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Electra's ``Dear Santa'' area asked girls to finish the
sentence: ``All I Want for Christmas Is....''
</P>
<P>
   One teen hoped for health and happiness for her grandparents and
her friends in Romania.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my parents to be happy and healthy ... And (for) all of
my cousins, aunts and uncles to be happy and healthy in the coming
year.''
</P>
<P>
   However, for herself she had a more immediate wish. She wants a
chance to meet pop group 'NSYNC ``so I can tell Justin how much I
love him. ... Oh yeah, and I want to be healthy and happy in the
coming year. (But) what I want for Christmas is for 'NSYNC to come
to my door and serenade me.That would be the best thing ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Some were hoping the new year wouldn't be too traumatic. ``I
just want my best friend not to be mad at me and my dad to get the
job proposal but not for us to move,'' typed one teen.
</P>
<P>
   Others had set up two chat areas: ``Family Members I Can't Wait
to See and ``Family Members I'll Be Hiding From.'' And you don't
have to be a teenager to relate to either discussion. Few teens
were looking forward to a swarm of grandparents aunts, uncles and
cousins all asking them how school was. ``Every one of my cousins
hides from (my aunt and uncle), and I'll be joining them this
Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Day looked like business as usual in the other AOL
chat rooms. Thirty-one political junkies took time out that
afternoon to log into AOL political chat room ``The Podium,''
continuing to argue about the Clinton impeachment scandal.
Conversation was fast and furious, and nobody stopped to wish
anybody a Merry Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we get real and deal with the struggle of everyday
life, there is just an outpouring of emotion,'' says AOL's Jesse
Kornbluth, who describes AOL's chat and message boards as ``a
national water cooler.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
