<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN. DEC. 27 --
NAPPY-HAIR, 12-25 -- Dwayn Catto, 35, one of only a few blacks in
management at a computer information systems company, was initially
ostracized by both whites and blacks when he dreadlocked his hair.
``My white peers thought I was out of my mind, and my black peers
thought I was a disappointment and an embarrassment,'' said Catto,
who saw the new style as a way to prove to himself and others that
he didn't hav to conform to succeed. (Norman Y. Lono/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SOLO, Indonesia -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- INDONESIA -OUTLOOK,
12-25 -- Supporters of Megawati Sukarnoputri cheer during a
campaign rally in Jakarta. The poster in the background shows
Megawati and her late father, former President Sukarno. Seven
months after student demonstrations toppled the country's longtime
ruler, Indonesia remains in precarious shape, with its economy in a
shambles, political reforms stalled, and the student movement
unappeased. (Seth Mydans/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- IRELAND-BARRY, 12-25 --
Irish author Sebastian Barry in the lobby of his hotel during a
recent visit. Although novelists have written plays, and
playwrights have written novels, it is rare for a writer to be
equally adept at both arts, with one standout being Samuel Beckett.
But at 43, Beckett's countryman Sebastian Barry seems well on his
way to such an accomplishment. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- PAKISTAN-JALAL, 12-25 -- At
first glance, Ayesha Jala, seen in this undated photo, seems like
an unlikely agitator. But in recent years, Jalal has taken on the
academic and political mainstream in her native Pakistan as well as
the administration of Columbia University, where she taught history
for seven years. While her historical work on South Asia has
elicited anonymous threats, it also earned her a MacArthur
Fellowship, worth $265,000. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- HURRICANE-MOVIE, 12-25 -- He
had done time in jail and been through the Army. He was closing in
on the middleweight boxing crown when race riots convulsed the
nation. He ran afoul of the police and was railroaded into prison
for life for a triple murder he did not commit. Now, 13 years after
he was freed through dedicated sleuthing and lawyering, Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter, seen recently, is reaping the ultimate
vindication. Denzel Washington is to play him in an upcoming movie
about his life. (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- CHEAP-CIGARS-2, 12-25 -- A
cigar rests on a wine glass at the City Wine and Cigar restaurant
in New York earlier this year. However the expensive cigar boom has
already peaked, people in the industry say, with a glut at the
upper end of the market. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Dec. 25, 1998 --CHEAP-CIGARS, 12-25 -- A
woman enjoys an expensive cigar at the Decade club in New York's
Upper Eastside earlier this year. However the expensive cigar boom
has already peaked, people in the industry say, with a glut at the
upper end of the market. (Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
