<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 12/25/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) LOS ANGELES -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- LA-CHRISTMAS-DINNER-2,
12-25 -- Elton and Betty White enjoy their meal at The Laugh
Factory comedy club which hosted free Christmas Day dinners. At the
mouth of On the Sunset Strip, the garish center of Hollywood's
nightlife, dreamers and castaways lined up under the California sun
for a show business version of a homespun tradition, the Christmas
Day dinner at the Laugh Factory. (Monica Almeida/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SAYREVILLE, N.J. -- Dec. 25, 1998 --
NJ-BUSCRASH-VICTIMS, 12-25 -- Lt. Daniel Cosgrove, of the New
Jersey State Police, speaks with George Black of the National
Transportation Safety Board on Friday while standing near the
damaged bus which overturned the previous day killing eight people.
The driver of the bus, which was on its way to Atlantic City, said
he was trying to avoid what looked like a patch of ice when he lost
control of the vehicle. (Chris Maynard/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LOS ANGELES -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- LA-CHRISTMAS-DINNER,
12-25 -- At the mouth of On the Sunset Strip, the garish center of
Hollywood's nightlife, dreamers and castaways lined up under the
California sun for a show business version of a homespun tradition,
the Christmas Day dinner at the Laugh Factory. This was the comedy
club's annual free Christmas feast for those have come far short of
achieving fame and stardom in the entertainment industry. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- FBN-JETS, 12-25 --
New York Jets Pepper Johnson during practice last July. Johnson is
the only linebacker still playing from that 1986 Giants Super Bowl
team. Indeed, he is the only current Jet who was with Bill Parcells
on both of his championship outfits. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- FBN-GIANTS,
12-25 -- New York Giants Amani Toomer celebrates a touchdown
against the Kansas City Chiefs last Sunday. Toomer's moves in the
end zone are eclectic, a half dance, half jump with a nervous,
excited hop -- a player having fun but certainly not in an
orchestrated way. No one could have practiced those maneuvers.
(Jose R. Lopez/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MCLEAN, Virg. -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- CIA-CHRISTMAS-3, 12-25
-- Philip E. Glover, background left, senior duty officer in the
operations center of the Central Intelligence Agency, confers with
Wayne Myers of the Foreign Broadcast Information Service section,
also located in this room. In many cities people spend holidays
away from their families because their jobs never stop -- like
those who handle foreign intelligence at the CIA and the domestic
equivalent at the FBI. The man in the foreground did not want to be
identified. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MCLEAN, Virg. -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- CIA-CHRISTMAS-2, 12-25
-- Lieut. Dave Lankford, a senior shift manager with the Security
Protective Service, patrols on Christmas Day through the main lobby
of the new Central Intelligence Agency Building, where, in
background, a memorial to Agency employees who have died in the
line of duty are honored. In many cities people spend holidays away
from their families because their jobs never stop -- like those who
handle foreign intelligence at the CIA and the domestic equivalent
at the FBI. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MCLEAN, Virg. -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- CIA-CHRISTMAS-1, 12-25
-- A view from above a display atrium in the new building of the
Central Intelligence Agency as an employee, one of the few who was
obliged to work on Christmas Day, passed models of agency aircraft.
Hanging from left are: a U-2, a D-21 drone and an A-12, the agency
version of the SR-71. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- CANADA-AMNESIAC, 12-25 -- All
James Edward Brighton knows for sure is that sometime after
midnight on Oct. 12, 1998, he awoke in a Montreal parking lot,
naked, dazed and without a clue to who he was, apart from his name,
or how he got there. The Montreal police have contacted the F.B.I.
and Interpol, but to no avail. Brighton is seen in an undated photo
posted on the Internet to aid in his further identification. (New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN. DEC. 27 --
NAPPY-HAIR, 12-25 -- Dwayn Catto, 35, one of only a few blacks in
management at a computer information systems company, was initially
ostracized by both whites and blacks when he dreadlocked his hair.
``My white peers thought I was out of my mind, and my black peers
thought I was a disappointment and an embarrassment,'' said Catto,
who saw the new style as a way to prove to himself and others that
he didn't have to conform to succeed. (Norman Y. Lono/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SOLO, Indonesia -- Dec. 25, 1998 -- INDONESIA -OUTLOOK,
12-25 -- Supporters of Megawati Sukarnoputri cheer during a
campaign rally in Jakarta. The poster in the background shows
Megawati and her late father, former President Sukarno. Seven
