</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-MARKIEWICZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR IN MEDIA HAD LESS LINGERIE, LESS GIFFORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The year 1997 wasn't an especially good one
for some members of the sports media, what with Marv Albert's
dressing, Gary Miller's tinkling and Frank Gifford's groping.
Things were a bit better in 1998, so our year-end sports media
best/worst list is appropriately kinder and gentler.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest TV loss: It came when Keith Jackson announced that this
season would be his last broadcasting college football on ABC.
Somehow, Saturday afternoons in the fall will never be the same.
Imagine anyone else introducing the game of the year with one of
those scene-setting, pregame monologues Jackson made famous.
Imagine anyone else coming up with colorful phrases like, ``Whoa,
Nellie!'', and those ``big uglies'' on the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Best TV comeback: Maybe it's having a new partner, Boomer
Esiason, in the booth. Maybe it's the motivation from having your
job constantly threatened. Whatever it is, Dan Dierdorf has had an
All-Pro season on ``Monday Night Football''. In recent years,
Dierdorf at times has seemed on auto pilot, but this season he
appears rejuvenated. His energy level is up, he seems better
prepared, and his comments and humor both have been far sharper.
Now, if he can only get off those bank-loan commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Most embarrassing TV gig: As noted, last year was a bad one for
former golden boy Gifford. That was mostly because of that ugly
off-the-field incident that got into the tabloids. This year wasn't
a great one on the air. Bounced from the MNF booth to a remote
studio in a Baltimore sports bar as a reporter on ``Monday Night
Blast'', Giff had little to do and he looked uncomfortable doing
it. Left to twist in the wind, he did manage to carry on,
preserving his dignity, if not his career.
</P>
<P>
   Best trend in sports TV: Sports documentaries. This year,
viewers have been treated to riveting specials on subjects ranging
from the CCNY college basketball point-shaving scandal in the
1950s, to the dark side of prize fighter Sugar Ray Robinson, to the
deterioration of Fresno State University's 1997-98 basketball
season. Encore! Encore!
</P>
<P>
   Worst trend in TV sports: The now omnipresent camera shots of
NFL defensive and offensive coordinators working in the booth
during games. What's so informative or entertaining about watching
some grim-faced guy sitting at a desk doodling on a piece of paper?
</P>
<P>
   Biggest I-told-you-so: The second-guessers had a good time when
George Seifert was supplanted on the ``NFL Today'' by CBS
executives in midseason. All along, skeptics had said the taciturn
former San Francisco 49ers coach was a bad fit for a TV show that
requires lots of arm-flapping and blather. They were right. Of
course, it didn't help that his sidemates, fellow rookies Brent
Jones and Marcus Allen, were equally unprepared for their roles.
</P>
<P>
   Most endearing interview of the year: After the Vikings'
Thanksgiving Day thrashing of the Cowboys at Texas Stadium, a print
reporter asked Minnesota star receiver Randy Moss for a comment.
Moss replied that he wouldn't, noting, ``You're not TV.'' So much
for that new, improved image.
</P>
<P>
   Most welcome return: Keith Olbermann, who admitted that he'd
made a move he could no longer live with when he left the field of
sports broadcasting for the world of Monica Lewinsky at MSNBC.
Which is why he has since returned to sports in his new job at Fox
Sports Net, bringing his special brand of sass with him. Olbermann
is on a long-term contract, so don't expect him to move to The
Learning Channel anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Most noteworthy book by a local athlete: ``Power, Money and
Sex'' by Deion Sanders. So it's not great literature. But how can
you resist a book that in its opening chapter leaves you dangling,
literally, on an edge of a cliff? And, really, who's better suited
to write an autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   Most ill-advised sports commentary: ``Kansas City Star'' sports
columnist Jason Whitlock, goaded by New England Patriots fans
during a Chiefs' game at Foxboro Stadium in October, displayed
two-handwritten signs from the press box in response. One read:
``It's warm in here _ good-looking women, too.'' The second
included the question: ``Bledsoe gay?''
</P>
<P>
   Second most ill-advised sports commentary: Locked-out NBA
mega-star Karl Malone going on air during his new sports talk radio
gig in Los Angeles and demanding a trade from the Utah Jazz, saying
he felt unappreciated. Some mail, Karl, is best left undelivered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
