<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6755 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TCUKICKER-TEX     12-25 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCUKICKER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROGS' KICKER WORTHY OF GLASS SLIPPER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU's football team boards an airplane bound
for El Paso this morning, a journey covering nearly 650 miles.
</P>
<P>
   But coach Dennis Franchione and his Horned Frogs have come much
further to earn a spot in a bowl game. In a span of a single season
and a single coach, TCU has gone from bowl wallflower at 1-10 to
Sun Bowl belle at 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches have names for turnarounds like TCU's _ Cinderella
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   And in a season loaded with feel-good Frog fairy tales, Chris
Kaylakie might best them all.
</P>
<P>
   Only instead of a glass slipper, Kaylakie has a golden toe.
</P>
<P>
   His fairy-tale season includes game-winning field goals and
all-Western Athletic Conference honors as a walk-on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris Kaylakie's been sort of symbolic of our Cinderella
year,'' Franchione said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaylakie came to practice last spring looking for a chance to
try a couple of field goals, a walk-on hardly hopes for anything
more.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione looked around and found he had few options. Mr.
All-World Michael Reeder had graduated, and Kaylakie got his
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew some areas where there were voids, no tight ends, no
kickers,'' Franchione said. ``It was one of the positions where we
were starting from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Kaylakie: ``I was just looking to make the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring proved to be less than expected for both sides, with
Kaylakie having an up-and-down camp.
</P>
<P>
   He remained TCU's No. 1 option heading into two-a-days because
few options existed.
</P>
<P>
   An ``unknown,'' TCU special-teams coach Mark Tommerdahl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to expect that first game,'' Tommerdahl
said. ``I guess you never know what to expect with a kicker until
you get them out under the lights.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaylakie had a 23-yard field goal in TCU's season-opening
victory against Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   In Week 2, he accounted for all of TCU's points in a 10-9 loss
against Oklahoma. He went 3-for-3 on field-goal attempts, including
a long of 43 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd get pretty nervous, still does,'' Frogs holder Jeff Dover
said. ``I think after Oklahoma, though, he learned that he could do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably, his biggest test came two weeks later against
Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   TCU trailed 13-10 with five seconds remaining. Franchione waved
Kaylakie in for a 50-yard attempt, which he booted through for his
longest field goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird to look at the highlight tape of the season, you
see everybody on the sidelines hands go up before it even gets
there,'' Kaylakie said. ``I knew, or at least I thought I knew, but
until it went through I wasn't sure.''
</P>
<P>
   He finished the season 15-for-20 on field goals, earning all-WAC
honors and acclaim from various newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``An all-around unbelievable season,'' Kaylakie said. ``It has
exceeded my wildest expectations and then some. I'm playing, we're
going to a bowl game. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Kaylakie, like all of his teammates, returned from a brief
holiday break, his presents already opened and forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Another awaits him, though, when he steps onto TCU's airplane
this morning. A late gift, so to speak _ Franchione plans to tell
him he's earned a scholarship for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very rewarding to see a young man who has in and over
considerable odds proceeded to earn the respect of his teammates
and coaches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
