<HEADLINE>
SMITH STILL SEARCHING FOR RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ On the Friday afternoon before the Cowboys went
to Kansas City two weeks ago, public relations director Rich
Dalrymple had a request for running back Emmitt Smith, who needed
one rushing touchdown to break a tie with Marcus Allen for the
all-time career mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The TV guys want to interview you just in case you break the
record,'' Dalrymple said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just in case?'' Smith said, laughing. ``I just need one.
Where's your confidence, Rich?''
</P>
<P>
   Smith still needs that one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   He has been stuck on 123 career rushing touchdowns since he
rushed for three on Thanksgiving Day against Minnesota. Because
reserve running back Chris Warren is out for the year, Smith will
probably get several opportunities to break the record tomorrow
night in the season finale against the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has 11 rushing touchdowns this season, fourth in the NFL
behind Denver's Terrell Davis (21), Atlanta's Jamal Anderson (13),
and Jacksonville rookie Fred Taylor (13). Super Nate The Cowboys
might be long shots to make the Super Bowl, but guard Nate Newton
guarantees he will be in Miami next month.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Cowboys don't make Super Bowl XXXIII, Newton said
he'll encourage a lot of his younger teammates to join him in South
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to know what it's like,'' Newton said. ``I went to
the Super Bowl in Tampa Bay \RJanuary 1991\S. Man, going there,
feeling that atmosphere. It inspired me for the next year. That's
where you want to be. You want to be the only one being watched in
the whole world.'' Garrett due a raise A loss by the Cowboys
tomorrow would void the final year on backup quarterback Jason
Garrett's contract and make him a free agent. A clause in Garrett's
contract gave him the option to become a free agent if he led the
team to a record that was better than the team's record in all
games at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett led the club to a 3-2 record when Troy Aikman was out
with a fractured collarbone. That's a .600 winning percentage. The
Cowboys, at 9-6, are at .600 now. A win would put them at .620, a
loss at .562.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the Cowboys win, the club could allow Garrett to
become a free agent and let him shop his services to the highest
bidder next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we end up with a better record based on percentage
points, we'd still consider tearing up his contract,'' team owner
Jerry Jones said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
