<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6758 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GOALIES-TEX     12-25 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GOALIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE RULES CHANGES, DOMINANCE IN THE NET PREVAILS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When the NHL decided this summer to trim two
feet from three sides around its goaltenders, rulemakers were
hoping to alleviate the league's biggest image problem _ a lack of
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   But in the face of the cutbacks _ which included cutting two
feet from each side of the goal crease and giving goal-scorers two
more feet behind the net _ NHL goalies are finding they have more
than one good leg left to stand on.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first 10 weeks of the season, goal-scoring is at 5.2
goals per game, down about .1 goals from last season. What's more,
two-time NHL most valuable player Dominik Hasek is making a run at
a hat trick. The Buffalo Sabres goalie has posted numbers obscene
to fans of offensive hockey. If his 1.72 goals-per-game average and
.945 save percentage hold up throughout the season, it would be the
best posted in the modern-day NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're proving it more than ever this season, the
goalies are the best players in the game right now,'' former Stars
goalie Andy Moog said.
</P>
<P>
   While Moog's assessment comes from the goaltenders' perspective,
it's backed by hard statistics and a few supporters from the
non-goaltender crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the systems obviously play a role, but I think you
have to say the goalies are getting better,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``If you watch games, there are some great scoring
opportunities, and goalies simply stop more of them. That's the
bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the goaltender's job is both easier and more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   It's easier to some degree because while scoring opportunities
appear good, they often come from the perimeter or as first shots
on odd-man rushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And those aren't the best scoring chances,'' Moog said.
``Shots are probably about the same, but I think real, legitimate
scoring chances are down.''
</P>
<P>
   The job is more difficult because the expectations on
goaltenders _ and the corresponding pressure _ is greatly
increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting now that one goal is like a mountain, especially
if it's a first goal or a soft goal,'' said Ken Dryden, president
of the Toronto Maple Leafs and a Hall of Fame goalie. ``That's too
much pressure. That's what happened to \Rformer goalie\S Felix
Potvin here. You can't play the game when there's pressure like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, goalies are playing well under the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't do it, there's several guys waiting to take your
place,'' Moog said.
OLDER AND WISER Patrick Roy led the NHL with a 2.36 goals-against
average in 1991-92, a season before he would lead Montreal to his
second Stanley Cup title with the Canadiens. Ed Belfour led the NHL
with a 2.47 GAA in 1990-91 _ the year he won the Calder Trophy as
rookie of the year and the Vezina Trophy as best NHL goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some eight years later, the goalies who are scheduled to
meet at 8 tonight in a game between Roy's Colorado Avalanche and
Belfour's Stars are punching up better numbers. Roy has a 2.19 GAA
and Belfour a 2.00, yet they aren't considered the best in the game
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the way of the NHL goaltending wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a better goalie than I was then,'' said Belfour,
33. ``I think you learn to think the game more, you learn from
experience. And now that I'm injury free, I'd say I'm in as good a
shape as I've ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy, also 33, is sending a message to those who felt he was
finished. Roy stumbled out of the gate this season, going 1-6-1 and
allowing 30 goals in his first eight starts _ a GAA of almost 4.00.
Since, he has a 1.57 GAA in his past 17 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all feel we're getting better,'' said Maple Leafs
goalie Curtis Joseph, 31. ``Goalies mature at a later age.''
</P>
<P>
   Improved training techniques combined with a better
self-awareness concerning conditioning results in a dangerous mix:
goalies who have the minds of 32-year-olds and the bodies of
25-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a real evolution,'' said Moog, who retired last
season at 38 after posting the three top GAAs in his career after
the age of 34.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in my day, you put the guy in goal who couldn't skate or
was too small to play another position. Goaltending was the last
consideration,'' Moog said. ``But as time progressed, more and more
of the good athletes wanted to play goal. More coaches started
putting their biggest players in goal. And as a result, you have
the goaltenders of today.''
</P>
<P>
   Those players include a nimble Hasek, the 6-foot-2 New Jersey
Devils goalie Martin Brodeur or the 6-3 Washington Capitals goalie
Olaf Kolzig. To keep up with those athletes, goaltenders realized
they had to condition themselves on a full-time basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you have the older goalies who are trying to keep up with
the younger goalies and the younger goalies trying to keep up with
the older goalies,'' Moog said.
</P>
<P>
   And the cycle of competition has improved the goaltender
position as a whole. Add to the mix the fact that the impact of
overseas goaltenders is catching up to the impact of overseas
scorers and you have an even deeper talent pool from which to draw
a netminder.
</P>
<P>
   While Hasek (Czech Republic) has won four of the past five
Vezina Trophies, he had been alone as a European standout in the
NHL. Now, Russia's Nikolai Khabibulin is shining with the Phoenix
Coyotes (13-4-2, 1.88 GAA); Kolzig (Germany) helped the Capitals to
the Stanley Cup Finals last season; and the New York Islanders
Tommy Salo (Sweden) has posted five shutouts this season.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, backup goalies such as the Stars' Roman Turek
(Czech Republic) and the Hurricanes' Arturs Irbe (Latvia) are
pushing the No. 1 goalies to get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more opportunities for goaltenders because of
expansion,'' Dryden said. ``And more goaltenders are taking
advantage of their opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The goalies have been so good, the NHL not only took two feet
from each side of the crease, it also started nipping and tucking
at the goalies' equipment. The NHL has tightened measurements on
all pad surfaces, and even pants and jerseys, which goalies were
using to take away precious inches of available net space.
</P>
<P>
   If you take a big guy and hang a big jersey on him, the net can
look awfully small _ something the NHL wants to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was needed,'' Dryden said. ``The equipment had gotten so
big that the shooters were losing confidence and the goalies were
gaining confidence. When that happens, you get a cycle that leads
to less goal-scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   And goalies, at least publicly, are saying they like the harsher
standards, although they're not so keen on the NHL fining teams
$100,000 and suspending goalies for one game without pay if he is
discovered to have cheated and used oversized equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't seem to worry about the shooters improving their
equipment, but I guess that's the game,'' Joseph said. ``Really, I
like the rules. Now, you know that everyone is on the same level.
You don't have to wonder about the guy at the other end of the
ice.''
</P>
<P>
   That concern was something Moog, generously listed at 5-9, said
he used to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were some goalies who obviously took advantage
of every opportunity to used bigger equipment,'' Moog said. ``And I
think some of those goalies are struggling now.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy has proven with his recent hot streak that the whispers
about his large pads might have been exaggerated. However, players
such as Kolzig and the Carolina Hurricanes' Trevor Kidd have
struggled, leading to some speculation that taking away their
bigger pads has resulted in mental adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about any player in particular, but if you had
big pads and you had to go to smaller pads, I think there would be
a mental adjustment,'' Moog said.
</P>
<P>
   But those players are the exception to the rule. Today's
goaltenders are instead eating up the NHL's repeated restrictions
and spitting them out like another puck that couldn't make it to
the back of the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goalies are just good,'' Moog said. ``They spent the past
four years changing the rules and trying to prove otherwise, and
they haven't done it yet. It's not too hard to figure it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-98 2142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
