<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6760 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-EDIT-MENDES-NYT &LR;      12-25 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-EDIT-MENDES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE CHICO MENDES LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to correct header coding. No text changes.)  (rl) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Dec. 26:
</P>
<P>
   Chico Mendes was not an environmentalist in the traditional
sense. It was only three years before his murder, which was 10
years ago this week, that he met environmentalists and learned with
amazement that the Amazon Forest mattered to those far away. As
head of Brazil's National Council of Rubber Tappers, his concerns
were the tappers who were being forced off their land and killed in
disputes with invading ranchers. But Mendes probably did more than
any other person to preserve the Amazon. Although it has been
burning faster than ever since his death, his ideas and
organizational skills have led to new policies and ways of thinking
about the forest that provide the basis for hope.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes was a full-time tapper at 11, the son and grandson of
rubber tappers. He led the local union in his state of Acre at a
time when small farmers and ranchers from Brazil's south were
invading the forest and claiming land, which they burned. Mendes
and a colleague, the anthropologist Mary Allegretti, came up with
the idea of extractive reserves _ forest land set aside by the
government to be managed cooperatively by locals, who kept it
healthy while gathering its rubber, nuts and other products to
sell. Mendes was shot to death by two ranchers who had claimed some
of the land marked for one such reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the disputes over land and the killings have diminished.
The federal government has set aside about 7.5 million acres of the
Amazon as extractive reserves, and some state governments are doing
the same. In the state of Amapa, which has been run for four years
by one of Mendes' colleagues, 30 percent of the territory is
protected and deforestation has virtually stopped. Amapa's
government buys Brazil nuts from the reserves for school lunches
and is helping to finance nut processing plants and other projects
to make the reserves viable. Mendes' allies recently won the
governorship of Acre state, and hold several Senate seats and many
state government posts.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes also created a lasting change in attitudes about the
Amazon, in Brazil and all over the world. He lobbied the World Bank
in a donated, ill-fitting suit, and the bank, which once financed
roads to make the Amazon easier to cut down, is now financing
extractive reserves. Brazil's government has ended its subsidies
for cattle ranchers buying Amazon land. It can now monitor forest
destruction, and has given more powers to the environmental
agencies that can protect the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes' allies are trying to hold back deforestation against
tremendous obstacles. One is globalization, which has brought a
wave of Asian logging companies to the Amazon. Brazilian rubber,
which now must compete on world markets, is too cheap to provide
the tappers with a decent living.
</P>
<P>
   There is also weather. The droughts caused by El Nino _ in turn
intensified by the destruction of the Amazon _ have dried out the
forest, allowing fires to spread uncontrollably. While last year's
rate of deforestation was a sharp drop from previous years, it
remains alarmingly high. In the 1990s, an area that averages the
size of Massachusetts has been burned every year.
</P>
<P>
   The preservationists must also contend with the clout of
ranchers, an important part of President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso's governing coalition. They have been able to gut many new
laws to improve forest protection and keep ones that have passed
from being fully carried out. According to Brazil's Catholic
Church, Mendes was one of 982 activists murdered in land disputes
in the Amazon between 1964 and 1988, the vast majority by ranchers'
hired guns. Eight people were convicted, all triggermen except in
Mendes' case. Even his killers, Darly Alves and his son Darci
Alves, who have since been recaptured, walked out of prison two
years into their 19-year terms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-98 2146EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981225.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FNB-FALCONS-NOTEBOOK-     12-25 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FNB-FALCONS-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    FALCONS NOTEBOOK
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Matt Winklejohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Falcons running back Jamal Anderson tends to fluctuate with the
best of them, at least off the field.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, he's been very consistent this year, with more
than 100 yards in 10 of 15 games. He is the NFL's second-leading
rusher, with a franchise-record 1,743 yards (trailing only Denver's
Terrell Davis, who has 1,830), and can set several more Falcon
marks Sunday vs. the Dolphins (10-5).
</P>
<P>
   Anderson also is near the league record for carries in a season.
He has 392, five short of Gerald Riggs' franchise record of 397,
set in '97, and 15 short of the NFL mark of 407, set by Tampa Bay's
James Wilder in '84.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson knows the Dolphins limited Davis to a season-low 29
yards on 16 carries Monday night. He doesn't necessarily care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want all the records,'' said Anderson, who is averaging 26
carries per game. ``I still want 2,000 yards. They better come to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Anderson early in the week. On Christmas Eve, he had
mellowed.
</P>
<P>
   What about the record, Jamal?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I'm going to be pushing (running backs
coach) George (Sefcik) about, saying I need so many carries,'' he
said. ``I'm a player. I do what I'm asked to do. If they want me to
play the whole game, I'll play the whole game. If they want me to
play half I will. It's not that important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Early inactives
</P>
<P>
   Safety Chris Bayne was named to the early inactive list for the
fourth straight time since he missed team meetings and was late for
a practice prior to the Nov. 29 game at St. Louis. Joining him on
the early inactive list are canter-guard Dave Widell (for the 14th
straight week), cornerback Darren Anderson (for the seventh time in
13 games since joining the team), and tight end Roderick Monroe
(for the second straight week since he was signed off the practice
squad).
</P>
<P>
   Western view
</P>
<P>
   This from the weekly NFL notes column in the L.A. Times, under
the headline, ``Potential Stiff of the Week:''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta quarterback Chris Chandler. If John Elway couldn't
handle the Dolphins' defense, then how can anyone expect Chandler
to? The first letdown for the Falcons after the illness to coach
Dan Reeves against a team with a chance yet to win a home playoff
game.
</P>
<P>
   Incentive aplenty
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Falcons, who cannot improve their playoff position
with a win, the Dolphins can assure themselves of a home field game
in the first round with a win, and that's on the mind of players.
</P>
<P>
   Miami is 7-1 at home, losing only to the Jets two weeks ago, but
just 3-4 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to know we're in the playoffs, but there's no doubt
we want to be at home,'' quarterback Dan Marino said. ``It's so
much easier to win at home in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Reserve middle linebacker Ruffin Hamilton, the former Tulane
star, leads the Falcons with 15 special-teams tackles (and a forced
fumble), ahead of running back Gary Downs (10), linebacker Craig
Sauer (nine), cornerbacks Randy Fuller and Elijah Williams (eight
each), and reserve linebacker Keith Brooking (seven). ... The
Falcons lead the NFL with 38 takeaways, and have scored 126 of
their 404 points, or 31 percent, off turnovers. ... Team officials
are cautioning fans who attempt to purchase tickets from scalpers
that counterfeit tickets are likely to be plentiful for Sunday's
sellout against the Dolphins. Fans with counterfeits will be
escorted from the stadium, with no refund.
</P>
<P>
   Turnaround
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons gave up 461 points before Reeves and Brooks showed
up before the 1997 season. Last year they gave up 361. This year
they'll give up 300 if they hold Miami to 17 points Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Doing it differently
</P>
<P>
   Friday the Dolphins signed wide receiver Lamar Thomas and
cornerback Jerry Wilson to contract extensions, meaning that their
undisclosed signing bonuses will be pro-rated over this year and
the remainder of their contracts, reducing each's impact on the
salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas got a two-year extension, Wilson a four-year extension.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, who have about $750,000 left under this year's
salary cap, are highly unlikely to follow this course of action,
instead committing that money to incentives earned by players this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Those incentives will far surpass that number, and the team will
carry over whatever excess there is and apply it to next year's
cap.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a six-year veteran, is tied for second on the team with
39 receptions for 524 yards and five touchdowns. He will start
ahead of Oronde Gadsden on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
