<HEADLINE>
TCU'S JAKSIC CAN'T FORGET THOUGHTS, SOUNDS, OF WAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ You start with the war. The basketball,
well, that can come later.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in TCU's Daniel-Meyer Coliseum, surrounded by banners
and basketballs, Vladimir Jaksic describes what a grenade really
sounds like when it goes off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not at all like it sounds on TV,'' Jaksic explained. ``In
real life, you can hear it in your whole body.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the things you learn while growing up in Zagreb,
Croatia, a proverbial starting line for bloodshed that has ravaged
that region for almost 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia's declaration of independence from Yugoslavia in 1991
began the violence that ended with almost 10,000 deaths that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of people die in war, people like me, and that's kind of
sad,'' Jaksic said. ``If I didn't play basketball, I'd go to war
and probably die.''
</P>
<P>
   So you start with the war, and realize sooner or later you will
get to the basketball, because, for Jaksic, both remain irrevocably
intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   He's a serious thinker sometimes, creasing his brow as he talks
of religious and political problems that plague Croatia even now.
``It's scary,'' Horned Frogs coach Billy Tubbs said. ``He's tried
to give me a little bit of a geography lesson. I don't understand
who's who over there.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a kid sometimes, too, grinning wildly when Horned Frogs
fans chant ``Vladi, Vladi,'' following his now famous long-distance
shots. ``He's a very, very good shooter,'' TCU guard Prince Fowler
said. ``Sometimes in practice, when he's on, you'll just stand
there and watch him shoot. It's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The palm forces the ball up, the fingers push it out.
</P>
<P>
   From the second Jaksic lets go, he's watching.
</P>
<P>
   Jaksic likes to watch his shot unfold, standing right where he
was when he released the ball until he sees it bouncing on the
floor beneath the basket.
</P>
<P>
   He watches, bouncing on his toes like a kid, his wrist hanging
loosely above his head, his fingers dangling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vladimir is your typical shooter,'' Tubbs said. ``He has yet
to meet a shot he didn't like.''
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a spot on the floor that Jaksic wouldn't shoot from,
although he likes his chances better when his feet dance along the
3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   He has made 36 field goals so far this season, and 27 of them
have been 3-pointers. He has made 44 percent of his 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   It was the shot that got Frogs assistant coach Brian Fish to
take notice when Jaksic played for Blinn College, a two-year school
in Brenham. It was the shot that got Blinn to take notice when
Jaksic was playing in Croatia. It was the shot that got the
Croatian national team to take notice when he was growing up in
Zagreb.
</P>
<P>
   He had a childhood a lot like that of his Horned Frogs
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   He learned to play basketball on neighborhood playgrounds. He
opened presents on Christmas Day. He learned English by watching
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that show ``Dallas'','' Jaksic said, laughing.
``Kind of funny, I end up here.''
</P>
<P>
   He always figured he would be playing for Yugoslavia's national
team by now, a dream held by most kids in his neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like being a member of Dream Team,'' Jaksic said.
</P>
<P>
   Only Yugoslavia had fractured into many tiny nations when he had
gotten big enough and good enough.
</P>
<P>
   He instead played for Croatia. Proof of victory, politicians in
Zagreb like to say.
</P>
<P>
   Jaksic merely shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the majority of people didn't want this war started,''
Jaksic said. ``It was all politicians, and it's all politics. It's
very easy to manipulate people when the economic situation is not
very good. ... But you can't explain to people it's economics. You
have to put in religious things and patriot things, so they tell
you that Croats hate Serbs and Serbs hate Croats. But that's not
really true.''
</P>
<P>
   Religious tensions remain in Croatia and Bosnia, and many say
that prevents the violence in the region from ending.
</P>
<P>
   A bit of normalcy has returned in Zagreb, Croatia, the hometown
listed in the TCU men's basketball media guide under Frog Facts
meant to introduce the transfer from Blinn College.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know, it says, that his hobbies are ``playing tennis,
playing guitar and watching soccer'' or that ``Jaksic is one of two
native Croatian student-athletes enrolled at TCU.'' Anita Lelas of
Croatia plays on the TCU women's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't say that Jaksic was 16 when the war began or that he
considers himself lucky to have been in Zagreb, where bombs rained
down maybe 50 times, instead of daily as in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say that to somebody here, they'd be like: `Oooh, 50 times.'
But for me, it was like it was normal, just another day,'' Jaksic
said. ``When you see first time, it seems bad, but then you see
people in Sarajevo, in Bosnia, in other cities in Croatia were
under bombing that went on for two years nonstop and then I think
of myself as fortunate to be in Zagreb.''
</P>
<P>
   In his world, Zagreb seemed like a safe haven, not as much for
what it was but what it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Jaksic says he didn't really understand that until he got to the
United States and saw what Americans saw on the news.
</P>
<P>
   He seems very far away then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, really, in war, everything seems far,'' Jaksic said.
``You think 30 miles away, you think it is far, because you are
still alive, you are surviving. That's good, that's all good and
it's not good at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you are used to people throwing bombs at your city, 200
yards from you, and now it's 30 miles, and you can't really hear
it, so it's good.''
</P>
<P>
   He's farther than that now.
</P>
<P>
   He needs only to look around at the banners and the basketballs
to be reminded of exactly how far.
</P>
<P>
   It's never far enough to forget, though.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
