<SLUG> BC-RAC-STRONACH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SANTA ANITA OWNER PLANS BIG CHANGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Frank Stronach, the industrialist and leading
racehorse owner whose first season at the reins of Santa Anita Park
begins today, lays out his radical plan for revitalizing the old
racetrack with characteristic self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the final analysis, when the dust settles, it should be a
win for the horsemen ... for the customer ... for Arcadia ... and
naturally it should be a good investment,'' said Stronach, who
became the track's chairman after it was purchased for $126 million
earlier this month by his Magna International Developments.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the only certainty is that when the dust settles, there
will be a lot of dust.
</P>
<P>
   Stronach's ideas include uprooting Santa Anita's picturesque
paddock gardens to make room for a Citywalk-style retail,
restaurant and amusement ``village''; eliminating the unique
hillside portion of the turf course and installing a second turf
course; building luxury suites and rebuilding the barns; and _ by
the way _ putting a hotel and condominiums on the fringes of the
320-acre property.
</P>
<P>
   So jarring are the proposed changes that, if they came from
almost anybody except Stronach (pronounced straw-nack), they'd
stand as much chance as a three-legged horse of winning support
from the thoroughbred owners, trainers and jockeys who are known
collectively as ``the horsemen'' in racetrack politics.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if the plans for a hotel and condos had come from
Meditrust, the Massachusetts-based medical-care and real estate
company that owned Santa Anita for the past year, they might have
frightened horsemen, who have long feared the track would be plowed
under and its valuable land developed.
</P>
<P>
   But because Stronach is Stronach, the as-yet-sketchy plans are
being cheered as a bold scheme for drawing fans back to the
64-year-old track that saw average daily attendance drop to an
all-time-low 12,251 in 1996-97 before rebounding slightly last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's certainly the best option we have,'' said Brian Sweeney,
a horse owner and trainer, and a former racing executive.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it is Stronach's self-confidence _ understandable for a
man who claims to have washed dishes in an Ontario, Canada hospital
before building the auto-components company that earned him a $43
million salary in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That confidence apparently infected the 30-odd prominent
horsemen who attended a dinner hosted by Stronach in Pasadena 11
days ago. They listened to his plans and, from all reports, left
without their natural skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   And part of it is that Stronach is a horseman himself, an owner
and breeder of hundreds of thoroughbreds and an acquaintance of
many Santa Anita owners and trainers, some of whom have worked for
him. Stronach announced his intention to purchase Santa Anita in a
press conference minutes after his Awesome Again won the Breeders'
Cup Classic at Churchill Downs in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's got a little more credibility because he is in
the business and it's obvious he loves horses,'' said trainer Ron
Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a man who's committed to horse racing,'' said trainer
Vladimir Cerin. ``When a man (owns) 300 broodmares, I think he's
looking for places for their offspring to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Stronach demonstrated his commitment to horses and horsemen when
he listed his priorities for improving Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess my three priorities are to improve the quality of the
environment for horses on the backside _ that means stabling, etc.;
a better environment for the grooms and people who work back there
_ better dorms; and we have to look after the customer, we have to
make it more pleasant for him,'' said Stronach, 66, who speaks with
the accent of his native Austria (imagine Arnold Schwarzenegger's
rich uncle).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the specifics of his ideas may be impractical. If the
saddling paddock is moved in front of the grandstand, as Stronach
has suggested, will there be room for a second turf oval around the
outside of the main track, as he envisions? If an infield chute is
added to the existing turf course, what becomes of the infield
training track?
</P>
<P>
   And can he really do all this for $50 million, the number that's
been floating around?
</P>
<P>
   Many believe Stronach, a first-time track owner in North
American (though he owns a racecourse in Austria), is merely
running ideas up the flagpole now, not expecting to accomplish
everything. Less important than the support of horsemen, in the
end, might be the cooperation of Arcadia city officials, whose
plush community is big on peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are encouraged,'' said Deputy City Manager Don Penman, ``by
the concept of creating a really unique use on this site that
interacts well with the track.... He certainly put a lot of
concepts on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Santa Anita, under Stronach's blueprint, would be
transformed from a stately landmark to a lively tourist
destination, with theme park-style rides in an equine motif (take a
ride through the history of horses and horse racing!).
</P>
<P>
   The idea, he said, is to lure the public to the track, where it
will rediscover racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People nowadays have a great choice of entertainment,''
Stronach said on the phone from his Magna International office in
Aurora, Ont. ``So it's got to be more exciting.... I have a concern
that live racing is deteriorating. At every racetrack I go to, it's
just old people, no young people.''
</P>
<P>
   The very idea of trying to draw fans back to live racing excites
horsemen who have seen other track owners stake their futures on
the convenience of simulcast and home betting.
</P>
<P>
   If reviving Santa Anita means some of its historic features end
up in a dust bin, that's a price many are willing to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like if you owned a Chevy Nova and somebody offered you a
Rolls Royce,'' said trainer Richard Mandella. ``What are you going
to do .... moan about losing the Chevy Nova?''
</P>
<P>
   Stronach, who doesn't own a home in Southern California, said he
plans to be at Santa Anita about one week of every month during the
meet that runs from noon today to April 19. A pair of lieutenants,
former Ontario Jockey Club general manager Rick Cowan and former
Toronto Argonauts president Brian Cooper, are on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, William Baker, who was Santa Anita's chairman, now is
its president and CEO, and Cliff Goodrich, who was Santa Anita's
president, now is its executive VP and general manager. Stronach
indicated major changes will wait until he gets to ``know where the
good people are.''
</P>
<P>
   No timetable has been announced for any of the changes. The only
difference fans might notice this season is in the admission
prices; Stronach hopes to institute a ``free'' general admission
system in which patrons would pay $6 for parking and entry but get
back a $4 food voucher and a $2 betting credit.
</P>
<P>
   That free $2 bet could be won or lost in two minutes. The result
of Stronach's ambitious plans will take longer to determine _
months, even years.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Sweeney, ``If they were (holding) betting on it, I'd
go bet on him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
