<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MEYEROWITZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAN MEYEROWITZ, 85, COMPOSER ON MORAL SUBJECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jan Meyerowitz, a prolific composer whose varied catalog
includes eight operas and many chamber, symphonic and choral works,
died in Colmar, France, on Dec. 15. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Meyerowitz's music, which is lyrical and dramatic, often
combines a neoclassical sense of structure with touches of
chromaticism that gives it a modern sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   He was drawn to subjects that raised moral or humanistic
questions or that looked at the contemporary world through the
prism of Bible stories. His second opera, ``The Barrier'' (1949),
has a libretto by Langston Hughes, based on his play ``The
Mulatto,'' and looks at racial issues in the South. Hughes also
supplied a libretto for ``Esther'' (1956), about the biblical
queen.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Esther, who saved her people from the genocidal
plans of Haman, clearly fascinated Meyerowitz, who had spent World
War II in hiding with the help of friends in the French and Italian
Resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the opera, he wrote a symphony, ``Midrash Esther,''
inspired by rabbinical commentary and entirely separate from the
operatic score. Dimitri Mitropoulos led the New York Philharmonic
in the premiere of the work in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Meyerowitz was born in 1913 in Breslau, Germany (now Wroclaw,
Poland), and studied until 1933 at the Hochschule fur Musik in
Berlin. He continued his studies in Rome, where Respighi and
Alfredo Casella were among his teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1930s he made his way to Belgium and France. When
the war ended, several French musicians _ including the flutist
Jean-Pierre Rampal and the pianist Yvonne Loriod _ performed his
works in concerts and radio broadcasts. He married a French
musician, Marguerite Fricker, who survives him.
</P>
<P>
   Meyerowitz moved to New York in 1946. He worked as an assistant
to Boris Goldovsky at the Berkshire Music Center at Tanglewood,
Mass., and later joined the faculty there and at Brooklyn College
and City College. He also established himself quickly as a
composer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Barrier'' had its premiere on Broadway in January 1950,
and was revived at several Italian opera houses in the 1970s and at
the Darmstadt Staatsoper in Germany in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ``Esther,'' his other operas were ``Simoon'' (1949);
``Eastward in Eden'' (1951), later renamed for its subject, Emily
Dickinson; ``Bad Boys in School'' (1952); ``Port Town'' (1960),
also with a libretto by Hughes; ``Godfather Death'' (1961), and
``Winterballade'' (1967).
</P>
<P>
   Among Meyerowitz's instrumental works were concertos for flute
and oboe, sonatas for violin and cello, works for small string and
brass ensembles, and several full orchestra works. He also wrote an
ecumenical collection of liturgical works that included Jewish
works, like the ``Hebrew Service'' (1962), and Christian ones, like
the Easter cantata ``The Glory Around His Head'' (1955) and the
``Missa Rachel Plorans'' (1954).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
