<HEADER>
A6779 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DAVIS-UCLA-LADN     12-25 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DAVIS-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS HAS NEW KNEE, NEW ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When her phone rang one evening late last March,
Lissa Hodoh thought her kid brother was playing a cruel joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't play basketball anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baron, stop pulling my leg,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't. Not about this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't play basketball anymore,'' he repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Baron Davis would play basketball again, of course. A sophomore,
he is UCLA's starting point guard, its best player and its floor
leader. But last March his world of hardwood and gym shorts had
been ripped apart by a torn tendon in his left knee. Life wasn't
over. But it was damned close.
</P>
<P>
   What followed _ reconstructive surgery, a new ligament and a
grueling nine-month recovery _ was the toughest journey of Davis'
life, filled with anguish and despair, frustration and pain, with
nothing much at stake except his future.
</P>
<P>
   But along the road to recovery a funny thing happened. As Davis
rehabilitated his knee, he remodeled his character. As his new
ligament grew stronger, so did his psyche. He became more observant
and more patient _ much, much more patient. He tempered his sense
of humor. He trusted perfect strangers. He re-evaluated
friendships. He matured.
</P>
<P>
   And eventually, Davis realized the rehabilitation wasn't about
leg extensions or range-of-motion exercises or agility drills or
wind sprints. It wasn't about his knee at all.
</P>
<P>
   It was about his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rehab is day after day after day, and you have to be real
strong mentally,'' Davis said. ``There were lots of times I broke
down. I had plenty of down days. I had plenty of days I wanted to
quit.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Davis was driving to his knee exam when he heard a radio report
that he'd been cleared to play. A few hours later he was diagnosed
with a torn anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee, the result
of an awkward landing against Michigan in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Dr. Steve Lombardo replaced Davis' torn ligament with
a graft from his patella tendon, standard procedure in
reconstructive ACL surgeries. Lombardo then turned Davis over to
Judy Seto, a physical therapist and administrator at HealthSouth
Sports Medicine and Rehabilitation Center.
</P>
<P>
   In the early weeks, Seto worked to reduce swelling, pulverize
scar tissue and improve Davis' range-of-motion with leg extensions.
As range-of-motion developed through the summer, endurance became
the focus. Then, in the fall, agility and aerobic conditioning were
priorities. The same items stayed on Davis' menu throughout, just
in different orders.
</P>
<P>
   Davis reacted to his first career-threatening injury with
understandable impatience. Each week seemed like a month, each
month a year. In May, for instance, he asked to do agility drills
that were months away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Higher-caliber athletes are used to having their bodies
respond,'' Seto said. ``They're used to saying, `I can.' When their
body doesn't agree, they don't know how to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Baron was hiking a 10-mile trail, and he'd always
say, `Are we there yet?' The first time he did agility drills, he
died. He realized he wasn't ready. But memory fades, and two weeks
later he'd say, `I'm ready.' He had to learn to trust that we knew
what was best for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the court, away from the rehab center, Davis didn't know who
to trust. Sure, he had Hodoh and his grandmother, Lela Nicholson.
UCLA assistant Michael Holton greeted him after surgery. Coach
Steve Lavin and the Bruins stopped by for visits.
</P>
<P>
   But the same people who had latched onto Davis and shared his
rise to stardom at Santa Monica Crossroads School and UCLA suddenly
became his harshest critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll never make it back,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're finished,'' they pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   Friendship was thick as a patella tendon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not glad it happened, but it was a humbling experience for
Baron,'' Hodoh said. ``All the people that praised him when he was
a superstar, well, when you get hurt is when you find out who you
really trust, who really loves you.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early months, Davis had daily sessions at HealthSouth
lasting 90 minutes to 2{ hours. But as summer arrived and his
strength returned, he was allowed to work out on his own. Out of
Seto's shadow, he drifted. He skipped workouts and gained 30
pounds. He concentrated on the finish line _ returning to action _
but dismissed the steps required to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Although surrounded by friends and family, he was alone against
the challenge of a lifetime _ and it was overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that stands out about Baron is the mental challenge
he had to deal with day-to-day,'' Seto said. ``We tried to kick him
in the butt. We all had talks with him. But he was disappointed. He
wanted to be further along than he was, and sometimes he didn't put
in the effort we wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It taught him a lot of patience, and more than anything it
humbled him. He's not an arrogant kid at all, but he learned that
he had to take a different approach, that he can't have
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, Seto passed a mediocre progress report to Hodoh and
UCLA assistant coach Steve Spencer. With a one-two punch, they
snapped Davis out of his funk.
</P>
<P>
   First, a livid Spencer cornered him in the basketball office.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later, Hodoh called.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really challenged me,'' Davis said. ``She told me to stop
feeling sorry for myself. Those two really had an impact. That's
when I broke through the mental wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Advice came from all directions, and he devoured every morsel.
His brother-in-law, Dean Hodoh, clipped articles about athletes
recovering from knee injuries, including one about Jerry Rice that
Davis keeps in his bedroom. At HealthSouth, Davis talked to NBA
players A.C. Green, Mario Bennett and Danny Manning _ each living
proof that ACL tears are not career-ending.
</P>
<P>
   After months of thinking no one understood, months of believing
his suffering was unique, Davis realized he wasn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had surgery one week before Manning, but his rehab went
faster than mine because he worked harder,'' Davis said. ``They
told me I could do it, and they showed me it could be done. Plus, I
saw the season closing in, and that's when I kicked it up.''
</P>
<P>
   He progressed from individual drills to light practices to full
contact in a matter of weeks, dropping 20 pounds along the way.
When Seto tightened the reigns _ when she refused to clear him for
the Puerto Rico Shootout, for instance _ he was disappointed but
not derailed.
</P>
<P>
   Forget 10-mile hikes and finish lines; he cared only about the
next step. There were no distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell Baron has matured,'' Bruins guard Earl Watson
said. ``He used to joke around all the time. Now he only jokes
around half the time.''
</P>
<P>
   So when her phone rang in the early hours of Dec. 2, Lissa Hodoh
knew her kid brother was as serious as he'd ever been.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way,'' he said, ``I'm playing tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   His knee healed, his journey complete, Baron Davis was back from
the brink.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what, Baron,'' Lissa said. ``When I see you on the
court, I'm going to start crying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
