   COMMENTARY: SCANDALS SANS BIMBOS NEED NOT APPLY
</P>
<P>
   NA674325-TNS-WIR BC-EDIT-MENDES-NYT 668 12/25,21:33 U K
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL: THE CHICO MENDES LEGACY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-98 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981225.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6866 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-MCGARITY-HN     12-25 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-MCGARITY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ In the first 106 years of University of Texas football, no
player had done what senior receiver Wane McGarity did in 1998. He
caught more passes (58) for more yards (1,087) than any player in
school history.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It also is likely that no player in school history overcame a
greater physical challenge than McGarity did before setting those
records.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Wane has done is phenomenal,'' said Texas coach Mack
Brown. ``There are a lot of great stories on this team this year
with Ricky Williams winning the Heisman and Major Applewhite's
freshman year at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think there is any story any bigger, better or
more special than Wane's. I think he has been the story of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 27, 1997, McGarity thought his football career was
over. He suffered a severe knee injury _ for the third time in his
career _ that day at Rice Stadium, and he knew the odds of
returning in 1998 were against him.
</P>
<P>
   McGarity tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee,
something he had done twice in his right knee. Major reconstructive
surgery was required each time.
</P>
<P>
   He also had two arthroscopic surgeries on his knees. No one had
to tell him the sacrifices that must be made to get back on the
football field after reconstructive surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at it statistically, some guys don't come back
after one,'' McGarity said. ``Most guys wouldn't even give it a
shot after two, and a lot of people would hang it up at three.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of work to get back to where you once were.
Just the pain and all that you have to endure is tough. I didn't
want to go through all that again.''
</P>
<P>
   But McGarity had someone else to think about _ 3-year-old
daughter Dominique. ``My daughter would watch games with me on TV
(in 1997), and she would say, `Look, Daddy. You're on TV.' And I
would have to tell her that wasn't me.''
</P>
<P>
   Those days of sitting with his daughter were the biggest reason
McGarity decided to give it one more shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That played a big part,'' he said. ``I wanted to do something
special for her. I wanted to be able to show her that if you put in
hard work, anything is possible. You have to keep your mind focused
in the right places.
</P>
<P>
   ``She works hard at what she does, whether it's learning her
ABCs or 1-2-3s. The principle is the same, and that's how I want to
raise her, because that's how my mom raised me.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never quit on something that you have your heart into.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity had one other reason for wanting to try to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell there was something special about to happen here
under coach Brown,'' he said. ``I wanted to be a part of it in
every way possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``But one thing that kept running through my mind: `Are they
going to want me? Will they even look at a guy who's had three knee
surgeries?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a senior, and I thought they might say, `That guy might
as well go ahead and give it up.'''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity said Brown gave him the option to do whatever he felt
was right. ``Coach Brown came to me,'' McGarity said. ``He said: `I
will think no less of you if you decide to quit right now. We will
keep you on scholarship, and you can concentrate on getting your
degree, if that's how you want to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity already had decided he wanted to come back. Whether he
could be the same player was less certain.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-9 and 190 pounds, McGarity wasn't a quality player because
of his size. It was blazing speed and cat-like quickness that made
the San Antonio Clark product a top receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Regaining those assets after major knee surgery is no easy task.
Rehabilitation is painful and grueling.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the spring, Wane was down and discouraged,'' Brown said.
``His knee was not in great shape then, and there were questions
with him and me whether he could play in the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity said the hardest part was the daily grind of rehab, not
knowing if it was going to be worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had a chance to get my speed back, but how much I
would have to endure to get there,'' McGarity said. ``I told myself
if I wasn't the same player with my speed and agility and the way I
make my cuts, I wouldn't go back out here.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity credits UT doctors with helping him make a quick
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Brown told the doctors not to hold me back,'' McGarity
said. ``It was their work that got me back out here. They got me
back in shape and got my muscles back in condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the main thing was my heart was in it. I took advantage of
the opportunity they gave me and went at it full steam ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   After two-a-day practices in August, McGarity thought he was
ready. But there still was a twinge of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all unsure until the first game,'' McGarity said. ``I
had gone through some good practices, but you still don't know for
sure. I had told myself all along if it wasn't ready by the first
game, I wouldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That day came, and I had a 100-yard game against New Mexico
State. That meant a lot to me. It showed that all the hard work and
all the pain that I went through was going to pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   It paid off in a bigger way than McGarity dreamed was possible.
</P>
<P>
   He became the first player in school history to gain more than
1,000 receiving yards in one season. He set a school record with
four touchdown catches in the Longhorns' 42-35 loss to Texas Tech
and caught the winning TD pass at Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wane probably had more big catches this year than any receiver
I've ever seen or been around,'' Brown said. ``Everyone knew we had
Ricky, and everybody was going to load up to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had not had the kind of season we had from Wane, we
would not have been as successful as we were.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity led Big 12 receivers with an average of 98.8 yards per
game and surpassed by two the record Mike Adams set for receptions
in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Add it all up, and it helped McGarity earn all-conference
honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have imagined that,'' McGarity said. ``All I was
hoping for was to come back and be a part of things in some way. No
way did I think I could come back and get the school record in
receptions and be the first 1,000-yard receiver here.''
</P>
<P>
   UT coaches told McGarity he could petition for a sixth season
with the Longhorns as a medical redshirt if he wanted it. But
McGarity has decided to make the Cotton Bowl against Mississippi
State his final college game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been at this school when it went through its low point,
and I've also been here for some major high points,'' McGarity
said. ``I think it's time for me to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think I've set an example for the younger guys. I
think I've left something with the younger receivers on this team.
I think I've left my mark.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Brown, who sees McGarity as an inspirational leader he
can point to for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came back, and he was voted the co-captain,'' Brown said.
``When Wane walked off the field last year, he didn't know if he
would ever play again. Now, he's going to the Hula Bowl and
probably will be drafted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a dream season for Wane. He's in the record
books and made All-Big 12. I'm so happy for him. Proper attitude
and hard work are why Wane played this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
