<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6867 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HOLDMAN-     12-25 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HOLDMAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
COLLEGE STATION _ Some think it's like being a dancer sharing the
stage with Fred Astaire; you might never miss your mark, but no one
notices.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Others say it's more like being former Tonight Show straight man
Ed McMahon _ smooth, professional and witty. But in the end, it was
Mr. Carson who got the applause.
</P>
<P>
   But Warrick Holdman is no background dancer or sidekick for the
Texas A&AMP;M linebacking corps. Just watch film of the Wrecking Crew
at work, and you'll see how valuable Holdman is.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Dat Nguyen, a first-team All-America choice, gets
much-deserved praise for his record-breaking tackling prowess. But
A&AMP;M's defense would have a huge void to fill were it not for
Holdman, the playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes plays in the backfield, on the corner, downfield
everywhere,'' said Nguyen, who won the Lombardi Award this season.
``We know we can count on him to make something happen all over the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   A 23-year-old senior from Alief Elsik, Holdman shows his
versatility and value in his numbers.
</P>
<P>
   He leads the Aggies in passes broken up (eight), quarterback
hurries (four) and forced fumbles (five) and is second in sacks
(seven) and third in tackles (95).
</P>
<P>
   He also is second to Nguyen in tackles for a loss (16 for
minus-59 yards).
</P>
<P>
   But it seems only opponents know how much damage he does. Rest
assured, Ohio State, which the Aggies face in the Sugar Bowl on
Jan. 1, has seen a lot of Holdman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The publicity doesn't matter,'' Holdman said. ``I've been
dealing with that for three years now. On my part, I just wanted to
make sure I went out on a good note, have the best year I could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach always tells us that the best players always get better
and they end on a good note. To win championships and any kind of
big games, the seniors have to be leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really took that to heart and told myself that I'm going to
do my part, play hard and do what I have to do to help the team
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Holdman had a solid junior season with 81 tackles (13 for
losses) and was stellar as a sophomore as well, finishing second on
the team with 73 stops (nine for losses).
</P>
<P>
   But he was determined to make his senior season stand out.
</P>
<P>
   Holdman says it's hard to single out a particular game he would
measure as his best performance, but the Southern Mississippi game
Sept. 19 was the most memorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the game I just totally told myself to just go out
and whatever happens, get after the ball, and I played a great
game, one of the best games of my life,'' Holdman said. ``I was
playing with no pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, I used to always think, `Be in on the tackle but don't
make a mistake.' That day, I said, `Forget it; just make the
tackle. Worry about the mistakes afterward when you watch the
film.'''
</P>
<P>
   There were few mistakes to worry about, if any. After posting
just two tackles against pass-happy Louisiana Tech the week before,
Holdman had 10 tackles, seven of them solo and three behind the
line, in Texas A&AMP;M's 24-6 win over Southern Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Holdman keyed a dominant performance by the Aggies. Southern
Miss managed just 34 yards rushing on 30 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good,'' Holdman said. ``That game jump-started my
season, and it went well from there.''
</P>
<P>
   By regular season's end, A&AMP;M had one of the top-ranked defenses
in the country, and its linebackers were the major reason.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen, Holdman, Cornelius Anthony and Roylin Bradley finished
1-2-3-4 atop the team's tackles-for-losses chart, with Nguyen (147)
and Anthony (100) ahead of Holdman in total tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of talk about Kansas State's linebackers, and
they might be the best in the country, but A&AMP;M's linebackers are
right up there with 'em,'' Texas coach Mack Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies get one more chance to prove how good they are next
week in New Orleans against one of the country's top offenses in
Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone against a lot of good teams and a lot of good
offenses in the last year. They're just another one,'' Holdman
said. ``We showed that we can beat a top team. That was one of the
things about A&AMP;M _ we could never win the big game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat Nebraska, and everybody said we could finally win the
big game, but they (the Cornhuskers) didn't have the season that
Nebraska had last year so everybody was saying they weren't good
this year, so the win was kind of tarnished.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then we beat K-State. How big can you get? And to come
back the way we did, I felt that it showed the team that if we
stick to it and play and believe in each other, we can beat anybody
in the country. That's what football is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   And Holdman has dreamed of how he would like to see it happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, to win the game would be the best part of a
dream,'' he said, ``but to go out and play the best defensive game
we've played this year, from all aspects _ tackling, running the
whole defensive game, so that people will say afterward, `The
defense won the game.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the dream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-98 2320EST &QL; 
