<DOCNO> NYT19981225.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6868 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PLUMMER-HNS &LR;      12-25 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PLUMMER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Quarterback Jake Plummer is more popular in Arizona than golf, more
precious than shade and more valuable than water.
<TEXT>
<P>
   What Plummer means to the Cardinals can't be measured in
statistics. His passer rating of 75.4 ranks 20th in the NFL. He has
thrown 17 touchdown passes and 20 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen quarterbacks have more TD passes than Plummer. Only
Indianapolis' Peyton Manning and Green Bay's Brett Favre have more
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   So why in the world did Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill sign
Plummer this week to a four-year contract extension worth $29.5
million? Did the heavily maligned Bidwill finally lose his mind
when he gave a 24-year-old, second-year quarterback an NFL-record
signing bonus of $15 million?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Christmas present to our fans,'' Bidwill said after
making his second-most popular decision since he moved his
franchise to Phoenix in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 was drafting Plummer in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer, who grew up in Idaho and led Arizona State to an 11-0
record as a senior, is a legend in the Valley of the Sun. Now, he
is a highly paid legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making what I was making, I was very happy,'' Plummer said.
``Money has never been a big issue. I've never been one to look at
somebody else and think I should get more because I thought I was
better than him.''
</P>
<P>
   With one game left in his second season, Plummer has become a
master of the come-from-behind victory, following in the footsteps
of such quarterbacks as John Elway, Dan Marino, Joe Montana and
Roger Staubach.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals defeat San Diego at Sun Devil Stadium on
Sunday, they will finish 9-7 and earn the last wild-card spot in
the NFC. They would open the playoffs against NFC East rival
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs aren't that big a deal for many teams. Playoffs is
such a foreign word to the Cardinals, it's not even in their
dictionary. Futility and ineptness are.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals haven't had a winning season since 1984, and the
last time they went to the playoffs, they played in St. Louis. It
was 1982, a season interrupted by a players' strike.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Cardinals made the playoffs legitimately was
1975, when Don Coryell was the head coach. The last time they won a
playoff game was 1947.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder fans stood in line for hours Monday to buy 7,000
tickets to Sunday's game against the Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona wouldn't be in this position if not for Plummer, who is
known as ``Jake the Snake'' in the Phoenix area. In 24 starts, he
has engineered eight comeback wins, with Sunday's 19-17 conquest of
New Orleans the most recent.
</P>
<P>
   In his late 60s, Bidwill has become magnanimous. He has paid big
bucks to re-sign such veteran Cardinals as defensive tackle Eric
Swann and cornerback Aeneas Williams and such No. 1 picks as
defensive end Andre Wadsworth and defensive end Simeon Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we can get on to other player-personnel matters as
quickly as we can,'' Bidwill said.
</P>
<P>
   There is a method to Bidwill's apparent financial madness. At
this time in his life, he knows he must spend money to win. More
important, he wants a new stadium with public funds. A vote is
scheduled in May.
</P>
<P>
   If voters turn down Bidwill, he might move the team. Nothing
like the hometown hero guiding the team to the playoffs for the
first time in 14 years to get the voters to say yes.
</P>
<P>
   First things first, though. The Cardinals just can't blow this
opportunity. They don't even have to beat the Chargers if the New
York Giants lose at Philadelphia. But the Eagles might be the worst
team in the NFL, so Arizona must take care of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what any other team does, and we don't
really care what other teams do,'' receiver Frank Sanders said.
``We have to be responsible for ourselves. We've got to win out.''
</P>
<P>
   The players sound as if they're on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get there,'' offensive tackle Lomas Brown said.
``For the respectability of this organization and for everything
this organization is trying to get done, we want to be the first
playoff team (in Arizona).''
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals are going to have their first winning record
since 1984 and make the playoffs for the first time since 1982 and
possibly even win their first playoff game in 51 years, there is no
confusion about who will lead them. It won't be running back Adrian
Murrell, who has rushed for 1,017 yards, or Sanders, who leads the
NFC with 81 receptions (1,039 yards).
</P>
<P>
   It will be the 6-2 quarterback with the bird legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to rely on anybody else,'' Plummer said. ``We
want to rely on our ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1997 draft, former 49ers coach Bill Walsh said
Plummer was the best prospect in the draft. He said Plummer
reminded him of Montana. Like Montana, Plummer is elevating Walsh's
reputation as a genius.
</P>
<P>
   NFL fans have just begun to notice what Arizona fans have known
since Plummer began working late miracles for the Sun Devils: He's
fearless and refuses to accept defeat. That's why he is so
unbelievable when the Cardinals need to come from behind to win in
the last two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we've been in a lot of them and I am getting used to
it,'' Plummer said of the comeback victories. ``But it's just a
situation where your back is against the wall and you have to
respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why I respond, but I do. There's really nothing
you can do except try as hard as you can and make plays. I've been
able to have some success late in games, and the guys around me
have, under my leadership, bought into the fact that the game's not
over until that clock runs out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They believe in me, and they work a little extra hard when we
need a drive to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals are still capable of exasperating
inconsistency. They were swept by the Giants. They almost lost to
the Saints last week. Their fans never feel comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The players insist they are getting better each week. If they
beat the Chargers, who are out of the playoffs but have the NFL's
No. 1 defense, they will enter the playoffs on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in ourselves,'' Plummer said. ``We know what we
have on our team. You have to think that way or else there is no
chance of it ever happening. There's a lot of us on this team who
believe that we can go to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of talent, young talent, and that's part of
being successful _ believing in yourself, believing in the guys
around (you). We've got that feeling around here. It's something
you have to do every day. It takes time. Great leadership by
veterans doesn't happen overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer is completing his second season, but he is acknowledged
as the team leader. One thing that makes him so effective is he
isn't afraid to make a mistake, and when he does, he doesn't let
that mistake bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting used to the system,'' he said. ``Earlier in the
year, I was really pressing and trying to make plays happen. I was
trying to force a few things upfield. Now, I'm more comfortable
with it. I'm more confident reading the defense instead of trying
to remember where my guys are. I'm playing with a free mind and
just having fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to have the right kind of people around
you, to remember you're going to have some bad games. Not just when
you're young but even throughout your whole career, it's not going
to be perfect every day. Teams are going to be scheming to shut you
down, and it's very important to keep your head up. If it was an
easy job, everyone would be doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, nobody is doing it like Jake the Snake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
