<HEADER>
A6869 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     12-25 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
FOR conduct unbecoming a division champion, the Dallas Cowboys have
been roundly scolded and even ridiculed. With a game left, they are
9-6 without beating a team that had a winning record when they
played.
</P>
<P>
   If the 'Boys can slip past the Redskins on Sunday night at Texas
Stadium, they will have won eight games inside their own circle, a
division so puny it has been called the NFL Least.
</P>
<P>
   Reasonable people might point out the Cowboys didn't pick this
schedule. They played the hand they were dealt, and if they didn't
always play it well, perhaps the critics can cut them a little
slack. We are thinking along the lines of a Christmas amnesty, or
possibly a censure, but short of impeachment. Some fans think the
Cowboys should be punished for calling themselves ``America's
Team'' for at least two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones, gradually overcoming his shyness, changed
coaches last winter, bringing in Chan Gailey, the offensive brains
of the Pittsburgh Steelers. Jones believed, and he had a huge
amount of company, the 19 points per game the Cowboys averaged
under Barry Switzer would not carry them to the Super Bowl. Of
course, he was on solid ground. What it got them was a 6-10 record.
</P>
<P>
   So here are the Cowpokes, averaging &UR;  &LR; 11 points over their past
three games and struggling to edge the helpless Eagles. Dallas had
to resort to a fake field goal to score the only TD in a 13-9
victory.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of clinching the division title, the Cowboys
suffered back-to-back penalties when their center, Mike Kiselak,
moved before snapping the football. This is more than a bad omen.
Seeing your center penalized for a false start is like having the
groom blurt out, ``I do,'' before the minister says, ``Dearly
beloved.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Broncos, Chiefs and Saints treated Troy Aikman so
roughly, he had the kind of out-of-body experience similar to that
of Jimmy Stewart in the movie It's a Wonderful Life. You would see
Troy jogging to the sideline, trying to adjust his neck, and
imagining how the Cowboys would fare if he had not been born.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the movie, you suspect the results would be pretty much
the same. After all, they were 3-2 in the games started by backup
Jason Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is no one can be certain what offense the
Cowboys have used lately. We only know it isn't the big-play,
big-risk, high-octane attack that made Aikman famous. They have
suffered a sharp drop-off in speed and talent among their
receivers. Their playmaker is still Michael Irvin, who has caught
one touchdown pass in 15 games. They throw less frequently to Irvin
in the really critical moments because _ you won't believe this _
someone is covering him.
</P>
<P>
   Under Tom Landry, the Cowboys practically invented the multiple
offense. Currently in fashion is the West Coast offense, used with
considerable success by the 49ers and adopted by the Packers and
others. The Cowboys can call theirs pecan fudge swirl, if they
wish, because it has no clear identity. You don't need four wide
receivers when you are throwing for three yards to the tight end
and swinging it out of the backfield to Emmitt Smith or Sherman
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Teams have blitzed Dallas up the middle, forcing Aikman to get
rid of the ball too quickly. This results in gains, if any, that
hardly seem worth the concussions Troy risks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Cowboys have a huge advantage Sunday night because
they face the Redskins, who have nothing for which to play except
pride. And, as any cynic can tell you, if they had enough pride
they wouldn't have lost their first seven games.
</P>
<P>
   True, the 'Skins have won six of their past eight, not bad for a
team without an owner and with a coach, Norv Turner, whose job is
in peril. Once one of the league's most bitter rivalries, the teams
despised each other when Landry ruled the Cowboys and George Allen
was the devious coach of the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   But both were long gone from the scene when the 'Skins finally
won the Super Bowl, with Joe Gibbs as coach and Joe Theismann at
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the attention focused on the Redskins has as much to do
with their next owner as the status of the team. The tangled estate
of Jack Kent Cooke made the ownership an issue, reminding us the
Cowboys often have had more colorful figures at the top than on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Before Cooke, there was Edward Bennett Williams and the crusty,
whimsical George Preston Marshall. All quarterbacks owe a debt to
Marshall, who signed Sammy Baugh out of TCU in 1937, and two years
later forced the NFL to adopt a rule assessing a 15-yard penalty
for roughing the passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't put in some kind of rule,'' George said, ``we are
going to get them all killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, among many, will tell you the defense still tries. But
some protection is better than none.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
